see the blackened, charred sails of the ship,
treated against weathering, but still darkened

02:01:29.432 --> 02:01:35.486
from the blast of the fireball, the wood itself
darkened and splintered in places. You can see

02:01:35.486 --> 02:01:43.370
that giant, burned U that marks the deck.
Everything is held in place. You're making your

02:01:43.370 --> 02:01:49.010
way to the guards. What are you doing, Jester? You
see Beau being led up by the guards towards the

02:01:49.010 --> 02:01:50.426
Throne Roost.

02:01:50.426 --> 02:01:58.523
LAURA: Okay, you can do it, Beau. Do I see the big
fire explosion too, as it happens?

02:01:58.523 --> 02:02:03.080
MATT: Oh yeah, you saw and heard the distant
(explosion).

02:02:03.080 --> 02:02:04.093
TALIESIN: Whitestone saw the fire.

02:02:04.093 --> 02:02:06.863
TRAVIS: (singing) Whitestone saw the fire.

02:02:06.863 --> 02:02:15.662
LAURA: Oh. Okay. I hope everyone's okay. Please,
Traveler, be with them. I'm going to start running

02:02:15.662 --> 02:02:19.650
towards the docks in disguise.

02:02:19.650 --> 02:02:25.974
MATT: Okay. The guards have now pulled you all to
your feet, and have begun to apply manacles to

02:02:25.974 --> 02:02:34.101
your hands. Not anything too aggressive, but for
the purpose of safety and to maintain the order

02:02:34.101 --> 02:02:41.832
within this community, they're particular and
careful. They also go onto the deck, and you see

02:02:41.832 --> 02:02:50.484
them beginning to collect the bodies of those that
were killed. Bouldergut is inconsolable and

02:02:50.484 --> 02:02:58.556
furious, and it takes a few guards to get her to
calm down. Avantika is having a conversation with

02:02:58.556 --> 02:03:07.313
a couple of the guards. You guys are being pulled
away from the docks, towards the city. As you are

02:03:07.313 --> 02:03:13.896
brought towards the edge of it, one of the guards,
adorned a little better than the rest, have a

02:03:13.896 --> 02:03:22.479
brief discussion. You overhear one of them say,
"Hold tight, apparently someone's going to get the

02:03:22.503 --> 02:03:30.729
"Plank King." While you guys are all waiting, and
you're going to convene with the rest of your troupe--

02:03:30.729 --> 02:03:32.966
LAURA: I'm not going to join them.

02:03:32.966 --> 02:03:34.519
MATT: But go and find the vicinity.

02:03:34.519 --> 02:03:35.608
LAURA: See what's going on, yeah.

02:03:35.608 --> 02:03:40.922
MATT: There are many looky-loos on the edges of
the shipyards here. The docks make up probably a

02:03:40.922 --> 02:03:47.193
good third of Darktow. Before you actually get the
edge of the cliff where the city itself is built

02:03:47.193 --> 02:03:52.661
on different areas and platforms, and the streets
all rise at a perpetual grade, as it is embedded

02:03:52.661 --> 02:03:58.056
in the side of the cliff. There are folks who are
looking over to see what happened. Usually this

02:03:58.056 --> 02:04:03.143
kind of stuff does not go down within the city.
You can see that people are excited, and worried,

02:04:03.143 --> 02:04:07.069
and making up their own stories, and what they
saw. One of them is like, "It was crazy! A demon

02:04:07.069 --> 02:04:13.662
"fell from the sky and slammed into the boat and it
was intense!" The rumors are going crazy.

02:04:13.662 --> 02:04:15.398
MARISHA: It was a Gwar concert.

02:04:15.398 --> 02:04:19.917
MATT: That's a 7th-level spell, Summon Gwar
Concert.

02:04:19.917 --> 02:04:24.742
LAURA: (old man voice) Did Avantika finally do it?
Did she finally do it?

02:04:24.742 --> 02:04:25.940
SAM: She's still trying?

02:04:25.940 --> 02:04:28.958
LAURA: I always heard that she was going to stage
a coup. Did she finally stage one?

02:04:28.958 --> 02:04:32.288
(laughter)

02:04:32.288 --> 02:04:37.839
TALIESIN: If I can take ten minutes of this time
sitting manacled to cast Prayer-- if enough of us

02:04:37.839 --> 02:04:39.480
are within 30 feet of each other right now.

02:04:39.480 --> 02:04:44.340
MATT: You can probably all-- they do round you up.
However, as soon as you begin to make any physical

02:04:44.340 --> 02:04:45.877
action towards spellcasting--

02:04:45.877 --> 02:04:46.848
TALIESIN: It's all vocal.

02:04:46.848 --> 02:04:47.800
MATT: It's only verbal?

02:04:47.800 --> 02:04:50.988
TALIESIN: It's only verbal. And I tell them.

02:04:50.988 --> 02:04:53.394
MATT: You tell them you're going to cast a spell?

02:04:53.394 --> 02:04:56.470
TALIESIN: I'm going to be healing everybody. It's
a thing that I--

02:04:56.470 --> 02:04:57.968
MATT: "No spellcasting."

02:04:57.968 --> 02:05:00.360
TALIESIN: (loud sigh)

02:05:00.360 --> 02:05:02.281
MATT: "Don't want any funny stuff."

02:05:02.281 --> 02:05:04.272
TALIESIN: All right, that's fine.

02:05:04.272 --> 02:05:05.581
SAM: Have they taken our weapons?

02:05:05.581 --> 02:05:10.728
MATT: They have, after manacling, taken your
weapons. The individuals are carrying them at

02:05:10.728 --> 02:05:12.946
their side. Not yours. They couldn't find yours.

02:05:12.946 --> 02:05:14.752
TRAVIS: I wonder why.

02:05:14.752 --> 02:05:23.215
MATT: They have your crossbow, and they've taken
your shield and your staff.

02:05:23.215 --> 02:05:29.088
LAURA: Am I within range of everybody? Could I be
in the crowd, but near everyone?

02:05:29.210 --> 02:05:35.223
(laughter)

02:05:35.223 --> 02:05:39.680
MATT: There is a small perimeter being held, but
you could get probably within 20, 25 feet or so of them.

02:05:39.680 --> 02:05:44.260
LAURA: Then, if I'm within 30 feet, I'm going to
cast Prayer of Healing on my buds.

02:05:44.260 --> 02:05:45.488
MATT: Okay.

02:05:45.488 --> 02:05:47.970
MARISHA: What? On your buds?

02:05:47.970 --> 02:05:49.196
LAURA: On my buddies!

02:05:49.196 --> 02:05:56.217
MATT: Make a performance check to see how subtly
you can-- no, this would be deception. Make a deception.

02:05:56.217 --> 02:05:57.884
LAURA: A deception check. Okay.

02:05:57.884 --> 02:05:59.292
TRAVIS: Come on.

02:05:59.292 --> 02:06:06.621
LAURA: Eight. Well, I hope those people are going to be
okay. They look like they're pretty hurt up in

02:06:06.679 --> 02:06:11.272
there. Some of them look like they're bloody. That
one looks burned.

02:06:11.272 --> 02:06:14.703
MATT: As you begin to subtly try and sneak your
verbal components of your spell into the

02:06:14.703 --> 02:06:20.698
discussion, one of the guards goes: "Hey! Sorry,
we're making sure there's no casting this close to

02:06:20.698 --> 02:06:23.549
"it, if you don't mind."

02:06:23.549 --> 02:06:27.903
LAURA: Makes sense. I just saw some were hurt. I
was trying to help out, but if they don't want it,

02:06:27.903 --> 02:06:29.420
then I ain't going to do it.

02:06:29.420 --> 02:06:32.601
MATT: "It's best not to get involved. Terribly
sorry about that."

02:06:32.601 --> 02:06:35.095
SAM: I want to hear more!

02:06:35.095 --> 02:06:36.730
MATT: Nah, that's it.

02:06:36.730 --> 02:06:39.700
LIAM: No! It was so good!

02:06:39.700 --> 02:06:41.807
TALIESIN: This is what you get for Counterspell.

02:06:41.807 --> 02:06:48.475
MATT: He's telling everyone, "Please, hold tight.
Don't worry. We're taking care of it."

02:06:48.475 --> 02:06:54.325
TALIESIN: It's just a cheek caress, then gone. Not
even a kiss goodnight.

02:06:54.325 --> 02:07:01.265
MATT: Anyway, about 30 or so minutes pass for the
rest of you. As make your way up the steps now,

02:07:01.265 --> 02:07:08.605
trying to jaunt, you manage to catch up to the
armored fellow, who now acts as the tip of the

02:07:08.605 --> 02:07:13.430
spear, essentially. Now you're flanked and to the
front, although the flanking has to shift as the

02:07:13.430 --> 02:07:18.732
space for the steps ascending to the Throne Roost
get only wide for one person at a time. You are

02:07:18.732 --> 02:07:26.579
being held at that point. You make your way up to
the Throne Roost, to the shelf of stone. There you

02:07:26.651 --> 02:07:32.858
see, standing at the edge, is the Plank King
himself, blackened curls still dangling around his

02:07:32.946 --> 02:07:38.803
massive goliath head, his long coat billowing
slightly with the bit of wind that's whipping

02:07:38.803 --> 02:07:48.462
around the side of the cliff face. The morning fog
is burning off of the nearby reefs, and you can

02:07:48.462 --> 02:07:56.146
see a little bit further out. The sky itself is
still dull gray. Looks over and goes, "That was

02:07:56.146 --> 02:08:04.170
"quite the display, wouldn't you say?" The guard
goes, "Right, sir. One of them, we found at least

02:08:04.170 --> 02:08:09.907
"someone running from the bit who says they have
information for you." He goes, "Oh yeah, no, I

02:08:09.907 --> 02:08:12.411
"recognize this one. Step forward."

02:08:12.411 --> 02:08:14.279
MARISHA: 'Sup?

02:08:14.279 --> 02:08:18.163
MATT: "So what's all this?"

02:08:18.163 --> 02:08:23.299
MARISHA: What, the display you just saw, or this?

02:08:23.299 --> 02:08:26.606
MATT: "If you don't mind, tell me what's going
on."

02:08:26.606 --> 02:08:32.047
MARISHA: I think you just won the lottery, friend.
I toss him the book.

02:08:32.047 --> 02:08:39.186
MATT: He flips through the pages. "This is
gibberish."

02:08:39.186 --> 02:08:44.297
MARISHA: I know. Luckily, one of our crew members
is smart enough, and he deciphered the whole

02:08:44.297 --> 02:08:49.821
thing. In there you'll find everything you need to
know about the coup that Avantika has been

02:08:49.821 --> 02:08:59.513
planning. Whispers about wanting to rule the sea.
She has been worshipping an outer-worldly being

02:08:59.513 --> 02:09:03.748
called Uk'otoa, left over from the Betrayer Gods.

02:09:04.697 --> 02:09:10.101
MATT: He glances through the paperwork, looks at
you giving him this sly grin, and goes, "You,

02:09:10.101 --> 02:09:20.372
"newcomer into these waters, spent less than a day
amongst our people and have already attacked and

02:09:20.372 --> 02:09:22.222
"stolen from one of our own, as well."

02:09:22.222 --> 02:09:25.074
MARISHA: I didn't attack; she attacked us first.

02:09:25.074 --> 02:09:32.782
MATT: "Well, we'll see what she has to say to
defend herself, as well. Hang tight with me here,

02:09:32.782 --> 02:09:38.318
"with these men. The rest of you, get the rest of
your guard. Bring her friends, and bring Avantika

02:09:38.318 --> 02:09:42.269
"and who else had survived that massacre up here to
the roost."

02:09:42.269 --> 02:09:47.328
MARISHA: You're going to trust the things that she
says? You'll see a U burned into the deck of the ship.

02:09:47.328 --> 02:09:52.300
MATT: "I don't trust anyone, and I trust more
those that I've mistrusted for years than those

02:09:52.300 --> 02:10:00.935
"I've only come to mistrust and know right now. So
we'll see where it all lies. Be patient. If what

02:10:00.935 --> 02:10:04.601
"you say is true, then we've got all time in the
day."

02:10:04.601 --> 02:10:06.116
MARISHA: You have time to read that book right
now?

02:10:06.116 --> 02:10:10.405
MATT: "I don't read a fucking piece of this, but
I've got a few friends who are more of a

02:10:10.405 --> 02:10:12.730
"page-turning type."

02:10:12.730 --> 02:10:16.701
MARISHA: Hey, you came to me, though. Why?

02:10:16.701 --> 02:10:23.191
MATT: "Because I wanted to see if you'd actually
do something. Remember, we don't turn on pirates here."

02:10:23.191 --> 02:10:28.386
MARISHA: What do I get when I'm right?

02:10:28.386 --> 02:10:32.419
MATT: "If you're right, then I'll judge you based
on the fact that you broke our law as soon as you

02:10:32.419 --> 02:10:38.935
"got here, and I'll weigh it versus how positive
this tells me. There's not enough, well, maybe you

02:10:38.935 --> 02:10:42.931
"and Avantika will find yourselves out there on a
pike of warning."

02:10:42.931 --> 02:10:46.797
MARISHA: How about we strike a deal right now?
Because when you go down there, you're going to

02:10:46.797 --> 02:10:52.588
see murdered crew mates and a U burned into the
deck of that ship from where she was trying to

02:10:52.588 --> 02:10:56.195
summon Uk'otoa.

02:10:56.613 --> 02:10:59.315
MATT: Make a deception check.

02:10:59.315 --> 02:11:01.848
SAM and LAURA: Oh god.

02:11:01.848 --> 02:11:07.351
LIAM: (whispers) You crazy motherfucker.

02:11:08.116 --> 02:11:09.638
MARISHA: 17.

02:11:09.638 --> 02:11:14.331
MATT: Okay. He nods a bit.

02:11:14.331 --> 02:11:18.105
MARISHA: So if you think you can trust anything
that she says before you get into the details of

02:11:18.105 --> 02:11:23.751
that book, details that we've already deciphered,
as we've been on the seas with her for quite some

02:11:23.751 --> 02:11:27.921
time, and the betrayal that we have seen.

02:11:27.921 --> 02:11:32.747
MATT: "So's this one." He snaps his fingers, and
you see a cloaked figure step out of the shadows,

02:11:32.747 --> 02:11:35.736
the same cloak that passed you on the stairs the
night before.

02:11:35.736 --> 02:11:36.965
TRAVIS: Oh, right.

02:11:36.965 --> 02:11:38.060
LAURA: Is it Jamedi?

02:11:38.060 --> 02:11:40.206
MATT: It's Jamedi, hood pulled back.

02:11:40.206 --> 02:11:42.736
SAM: Is he with us?

02:11:42.736 --> 02:11:44.312
LAURA: I like Jamedi.

02:11:44.312 --> 02:11:45.945
TRAVIS: Jamedi does not like her.

02:11:45.945 --> 02:11:50.815
MATT: At which point, the Plank King steps up
towards you, now looming over you, a good two and

02:11:50.815 --> 02:11:57.594
a half feet of height on you. This imposing
presence, wide like a mountain, glancing down at

02:11:57.594 --> 02:12:02.400
you with a grin. You can smell his early morning
breath of rotting teeth and whatever he had the

02:12:02.400 --> 02:12:12.542
night before pulsing from his grin. He goes, "I
have to say, for someone so small, you've got some

02:12:12.542 --> 02:12:14.075
"serious balls."

02:12:15.810 --> 02:12:18.760
MARISHA: Thanks. That's not the first time I've
heard that.

02:12:18.760 --> 02:12:25.441
MATT: "And if you survive, I'm sure it won't be
the last. All right. Let's go see your friends."

02:12:25.441 --> 02:12:35.407
MARISHA: Hey! I want a boat, and safe passage out
if we're correct.

02:12:35.407 --> 02:12:43.220
MATT: "If this is right, let's hope you didn't
blow up too much of <i>her</i> boat; it'll be yours."

02:12:43.220 --> 02:12:45.867
MARISHA: Deal.

02:12:45.867 --> 02:12:49.743
MATT: "<i>If</i> it's enough."

02:12:49.743 --> 02:12:55.470
TRAVIS: Oh god. (choking)

02:12:55.470 --> 02:12:58.953
MATT: The guards now turn and spin you around and
push you back down the stairs as the Plank King

02:12:58.953 --> 02:13:05.534
follows behind, Jamedi keeping a close watch. He
goes and shouts something off to the side. He

02:13:05.534 --> 02:13:13.034
goes, "Solon! I'm going to need your brain for
this one. Come on." You hear a voice go, "All

02:13:13.034 --> 02:13:14.268
"right, I'm coming."

02:13:14.268 --> 02:13:16.669
LIAM and TRAVIS: Solon?

02:13:16.669 --> 02:13:25.561
MATT: Solon. S-O-L-O-N. Coming around the corner,
you see a human man, probably in his late 50s,

02:13:25.561 --> 02:13:35.159
early 60s. Bit of an unkept puff of a chin goatee,
his hair thinning in this big widow's peak, gray

02:13:35.159 --> 02:13:46.260
to white. These big spectacles around his eyes,
and this tattered, thin mustache that's attempted

02:13:46.260 --> 02:13:52.187
to be curled into a handlebar, but it seems to
have split in places and is not very well kept. He

02:13:52.187 --> 02:13:57.976
has this big, green cloak that's wrapped around
his shoulders that is so much material and

02:13:57.976 --> 02:14:03.332
billowing so widely, it makes his head
comparatively look much smaller. He's clutching a

02:14:03.332 --> 02:14:08.330
bag, and he's getting his stuff. "Wait here, I'm
getting my stuff. Ugh!" They keep walking, and

02:14:08.330 --> 02:14:13.227
eventually you see him trying to catch up from
behind. (panting) You take it this was probably

02:14:13.227 --> 02:14:16.568
what the Plank King was referring to as his
bookish friend.

02:14:16.568 --> 02:14:17.939
TRAVIS: You think?

02:14:17.939 --> 02:14:19.381
LIAM: Yeah.

02:14:19.381 --> 02:14:22.332
TRAVIS: He's the fighter.

02:14:24.346 --> 02:14:28.372
MATT: As you guys are all patiently waiting here,
looking amongst yourselves, is there anything you

02:14:28.372 --> 02:14:37.080
wish to do, or are you succumbing to the hope that
Jester, Beauregard, and/or possibly the Plank King

02:14:37.080 --> 02:14:41.645
comes to situate this? Eventually, you see
Avantika brought up from the ship in manacles, as well.

02:14:41.645 --> 02:14:46.017
LIAM: Well, I've noticed that they're not letting
any of us cast anything, correct?

02:14:46.017 --> 02:14:48.117
MATT: No, they shut that down.

02:14:48.117 --> 02:14:50.743
LIAM: Then no. I would do Mage Armor, but no.

02:14:50.743 --> 02:14:53.479
TALIESIN: This is basically a short rest? Is this
what this is?

02:14:53.479 --> 02:14:55.196
MATT: It's not quite long enough to be a short
rest.

02:14:55.196 --> 02:14:56.202
LIAM: Motherfucker.

02:14:56.202 --> 02:14:57.903
TRAVIS: I know, I was going to say the same
thing.

02:14:57.903 --> 02:15:01.572
MATT: Actually, you know what? No, it's about an
hour of short rest. I give that to you.

02:15:01.572 --> 02:15:02.620
TRAVIS: Bless you, Mercer.

02:15:02.620 --> 02:15:04.996
MATT: For the travel of Beau to the front, and the
rest of the guard to get there; for the Plank King

02:15:04.996 --> 02:15:07.751
conversation; for him to descend the Throne Roost
to make his way through the city to the docks;

02:15:07.751 --> 02:15:08.986
yeah, that's over an hour.

02:15:08.986 --> 02:15:14.240
LIAM: Then in these circumstances, I would dismiss
Frumpkin from the Material Plane and bring him

02:15:14.240 --> 02:15:17.075
back on my shoulder, so he's with me.

02:15:17.075 --> 02:15:23.965
MATT: Okay. As Frumpkin appears on the shoulder,
one of the watch goes, "Oh, where'd you come from,

02:15:23.965 --> 02:15:28.645
"little one? Didn't even see you come in." Begins
scritching Frumpkin.

02:15:28.645 --> 02:15:32.008
LIAM: He's friendly. That's my pet cat.

02:15:32.008 --> 02:15:35.698
MATT: Doesn't even talk to you. Just looks at
Frumpkin. "Who's a cute little kitty? We don't get

02:15:35.698 --> 02:15:39.688
"cats much on this island. It's good to see one.
Wonder what ship you came aboard?"

02:15:39.688 --> 02:15:43.471
(laughter)

02:15:43.471 --> 02:15:45.702
LIAM: I'm thinking really bad thoughts.

02:15:48.431 --> 02:15:55.647
MATT: Eventually, as the crowd begins to part, you
see a number of the guard, a few of the bodyguards

02:15:55.647 --> 02:16:00.244
that you had seen previously sitting amongst the
shadows of the Throne Roost when you first arrived

02:16:00.244 --> 02:16:08.387
the night before. You guys came roaring into this
town; you definitely did. There you see Beauregard

02:16:08.387 --> 02:16:15.844
being flanked by three guards, one better-armored
than the others, and then there, stepping behind

02:16:15.844 --> 02:16:27.772
that, the looming figure of the Plank King. He
approaches. "So not here but 24 hours and you've

02:16:27.772 --> 02:16:36.018
"already made a mess of our little home, have you?
I could see the flames from my Roost. My crow's

02:16:36.018 --> 02:16:42.639
"men tell me they spotted you walking aboard the
Squalleater and assault Avantika, one of our own.

02:16:42.639 --> 02:16:51.481
"Apparently a few of you fleeing into the city. You
know I have my misgivings about trusting anyone,

02:16:51.481 --> 02:16:57.484
"but I'm far more likely to toss in with those that
I've mistrusted long enough to at least know where

02:16:57.484 --> 02:17:08.496
"they stand. I don't know a fucking bit about all
of you. So my other friend--" and he points

02:17:08.496 --> 02:17:16.281
towards Jamedi, who's now in the back, and the
rest of you see, "-- says that you've all come in

02:17:16.440 --> 02:17:22.944
"with her lot naught but maybe two weeks back, and
that not most of you have much of an experience on

02:17:22.944 --> 02:17:32.790
"the sea, naught but one. The rest of you still
haven't quite found your legs on the waters. I'm

02:17:32.790 --> 02:17:42.660
"going to ask you right now, what brought you out
there, to mucking with the pirates' deals? Speak up!"

02:17:43.557 --> 02:17:51.428
TRAVIS: We understand your distrust. We are new
here, and we only beg your patience as we prove

02:17:51.428 --> 02:18:01.039
ourselves before you. Avantika and her crew were
up to foul deeds. Our friend Beau here, I trust,

02:18:01.039 --> 02:18:06.963
has shown you her journal.

02:18:08.050 --> 02:18:13.057
MATT: He reaches back in his pocket and goes, "Oh,
right. Here," and gives it to Solon, who goes,

02:18:13.057 --> 02:18:19.760
"Oh, all right. This is not a language I really
know--"

02:18:19.760 --> 02:18:21.300
MARISHA: There's a cipher in the front.

02:18:21.300 --> 02:18:22.111
MATT: "Oh, yeah."

02:18:22.111 --> 02:18:23.664
LIAM: Yeah, it's wedged into the back page.

02:18:23.664 --> 02:18:27.491
MATT: He takes it and pulls it out, looks at it.
"Oh, fuck me, this is--"

02:18:27.491 --> 02:18:29.942
MARISHA: Yeah, it's pretty good work, right?

02:18:30.895 --> 02:18:36.448
MATT: "Sir, with all due respect, it's going to
take me a long while to do this. This is elaborate."

02:18:36.448 --> 02:18:39.457
MARISHA: I told you, yeah.

02:18:39.797 --> 02:18:44.402
TALIESIN: I think there's already some work that
can be checked, if that speeds it up. I mean, that

02:18:44.402 --> 02:18:45.550
should be--

02:18:45.550 --> 02:18:46.866
MATT: The Plank King goes, "Shh."

02:18:46.866 --> 02:18:49.369
TALIESIN: Oh, yeah.

02:18:49.369 --> 02:18:55.306
MATT: "You said there's some special parts here,
of looking to overturn me or something? What pages

02:18:55.366 --> 02:18:57.235
"are that at?"

02:18:57.235 --> 02:19:02.639
LIAM: Excuse me, I am the one who deciphered this.
That is near the end.

02:19:02.639 --> 02:19:04.695
MARISHA: He's our Solon.

02:19:05.057 --> 02:19:10.009
MATT: Solon goes, "Oh! I'd very much like to have
a conversation with you."

02:19:10.009 --> 02:19:15.646
LIAM: As you will, if that is welcome here, but
yeah. The bit about her being a traitor to the

02:19:15.646 --> 02:19:23.283
Plank King, and wanting to rule over the entire
sea, and have the Plank King-- I believe the words

02:19:23.283 --> 02:19:30.855
are, if I remember correctly, because my memory is
spotty, "bend the knee."

02:19:30.855 --> 02:19:32.473
MATT: You point out the space where that was.

02:19:32.473 --> 02:19:34.231
LIAM: Is near the end, <i>ja</i>, right here.

02:19:34.231 --> 02:19:35.672
MATT: Thumbs through, and he goes--

02:19:35.672 --> 02:19:36.426
LIAM: It's complex.

02:19:36.426 --> 02:19:45.068
MATT: "Okay. O great king, give me a bit of time
with this, if you don't mind?" He looks around.

02:19:45.068 --> 02:19:50.701
Everyone's looking at him. At this moment he
glances around and sees the dozens and dozens of

02:19:50.701 --> 02:19:53.931
eyes locked on him, and he starts getting a little
nervous. You see a little sweat drop on his

02:19:53.931 --> 02:19:58.302
forehead, and he adjusts his glasses again.
They're starting to fog a bit. He goes, (clears

02:19:58.302 --> 02:20:02.439
throat), plops down, and starts going through, and
pulls out paper and a quill. He sets up in the

02:20:02.439 --> 02:20:07.086
middle of the dock area and starts going through
and point-by-point deciphering and translating

02:20:07.086 --> 02:20:10.754
each part of the cipher over to one of his empty
pages.

02:20:10.754 --> 02:20:13.847
TRAVIS: Great king, if we may, time we have.

02:20:13.847 --> 02:20:15.796
MATT: "That we do."

02:20:15.796 --> 02:20:23.088
TRAVIS: It's at your whim that we serve. I think
it would be only fair to ask that we remain under

02:20:23.088 --> 02:20:27.465
guard while your compatriot here translates that
text.

02:20:27.465 --> 02:20:29.267
MATT: "Oh, we're standing right here."

02:20:29.267 --> 02:20:31.088
TRAVIS: Fair enough.

02:20:31.088 --> 02:20:37.177
MATT: "You still haven't answered my question.
What brought you to these waters? Why'd you throw

02:20:37.177 --> 02:20:41.335
"in with her lot?" You see now, they're bringing
Avantika forward with the rest of you.

02:20:41.335 --> 02:20:50.924
MARISHA: Well, we're from Wildemount. Hired
mercenaries from the Empire. I'm with a secret

02:20:50.924 --> 02:21:04.688
order of the monks from the Cobalt Soul, known as
the Expositors. Avantika has been a person of

02:21:04.688 --> 02:21:10.999
interest that we've been wanting to investigate
for some time, and I was sent to do that. So,

02:21:10.999 --> 02:21:18.465
unfortunately, our business has nothing to do with
you fine folk here of Darktow. It only has to deal

02:21:18.465 --> 02:21:26.499
with Avantika. She's disrupted our shores enough.
We decided to investigate.

02:21:26.499 --> 02:21:29.678
MATT: "Where does your allegiance lie?"

02:21:29.678 --> 02:21:38.921
MARISHA: My allegiance is completely separate and
isolated from any persons here. My allegiance is

02:21:38.921 --> 02:21:42.437
with the Cobalt Soul.

02:21:42.437 --> 02:21:50.433
MATT: His eyes narrow. Make a deception check.
I'll say with advantage because you did drop the

02:21:50.433 --> 02:21:56.973
Cobalt Soul. In particular with the Plank King,
that has meaning.

02:21:56.973 --> 02:21:59.039
LIAM: I would like to read her as well.

02:21:59.039 --> 02:22:01.193
MATT: Insight check.

02:22:01.193 --> 02:22:02.676
LIAM: At disadvantage.

02:22:02.676 --> 02:22:04.202
MATT: Yes, for you.

02:22:04.202 --> 02:22:07.575
MARISHA: 22.

02:22:07.575 --> 02:22:11.846
MATT: The Plank King nods and goes--

02:22:11.846 --> 02:22:14.070
MARISHA: My voice is shaking. I'm so nervous.

02:22:14.070 --> 02:22:15.584
LIAM: 22 for me.

02:22:15.584 --> 02:22:24.288
MATT: Yeah, you barely see through. There's a hint
of truth, and there's a hint of not so true. It's

02:22:24.288 --> 02:22:25.848
a half-truth.

02:22:25.848 --> 02:22:29.246
LIAM: Caleb sees it! Go away, Fjord! Go away!

02:22:29.246 --> 02:22:32.632
MARISHA: Mixed lies or half-truths.

02:22:32.632 --> 02:22:37.926
MATT: The Plank King nods and goes, "Ah, the
Archives. I've had some dealings."

02:22:37.926 --> 02:22:41.635
MARISHA: Hmm. So you have your library card?

02:22:41.635 --> 02:22:54.316
MATT: "Not much of a reader. But your folk have
done good work for our interests in the past. So!

02:22:54.316 --> 02:23:00.992
"It's the woman of the hour. What have you to say
about yourself when these strangers have come

02:23:00.992 --> 02:23:05.829
"waltzing into our little haven and causing all
sorts of ruckus. Murdering your crew and making

02:23:05.829 --> 02:23:17.310
"these claims against you. Known you for years."
Avantika, hand behind in shackles goes, "Well."

02:23:17.310 --> 02:23:25.714
Her face, you can see bits where dirt, sweat lines
have made their way across and down the sides of

02:23:25.714 --> 02:23:32.300
her chin and jaw. Looking intently at the rest of
you with a forced smile through her teeth, there

02:23:32.307 --> 02:23:40.081
is a look of murderous rage and loss in her eyes,
as you have murdered a majority of her crew. She

02:23:40.136 --> 02:23:51.280
goes, "Well, I can guarantee that I kept no
journal. They came to me at sea with discussion of

02:23:51.280 --> 02:24:00.382
"perhaps coming and joining my crew, looking for
means of aid and gold. They began to talk of this

02:24:00.382 --> 02:24:13.421
"strange entity, this Uk'otoa. Well, I followed
suit. I wanted to make for some kind of alliance.

02:24:13.421 --> 02:24:20.152
"I found particular interest with one of their
individuals." She looks over towards Fjord, "But

02:24:20.152 --> 02:24:26.917
"it seems such a romance was merely just another
way to try and toss me to the proverbial wolves,

02:24:26.917 --> 02:24:35.606
"or merrow if it will. They've now killed my crew.
They've taken a number of my things, damaged my

02:24:35.606 --> 02:24:44.136
"ship, and they're trying to smear my name. One who
has walked alongside you and all of you fine, fine

02:24:44.136 --> 02:24:51.558
"folks for the past ten years! Even using the
memory of Vandren against me." You hear a few

02:24:51.558 --> 02:25:01.794
voices go like, (murmuring) "Vandren." "Vandren
raised this one and he sabotaged his ship. Blew it

02:25:01.794 --> 02:25:08.294
"asunder in the middle of the ocean. That was the
last he was seen. He's already killed one of our

02:25:08.294 --> 02:25:12.508
"own. Is this untrue?"

02:25:12.508 --> 02:25:14.849
TRAVIS: (stuttering) Is she talking to me?

02:25:14.849 --> 02:25:15.545
MATT: Yeah.

02:25:15.545 --> 02:25:20.697
LAURA: From the crowd, I'm going to go: She's
lying! We always knew she had it in for the Plank King!

02:25:20.697 --> 02:25:24.961
MATT: Someone goes, "Shh!" All eyes are on you.

02:25:24.961 --> 02:25:30.006
TRAVIS: Plank King, if I may. My ears, though
pointy, can only stand a certain amount of

02:25:30.006 --> 02:25:36.492
dishonesty. I would prefer to cut through the
bull. There are those of us among us who can make

02:25:36.492 --> 02:25:44.830
sure that the truth is spoken here. I would beg of
you to allow that to happen now.

02:25:44.830 --> 02:25:47.475
MATT: Make a persuasion check.

02:25:51.235 --> 02:25:52.665
TRAVIS: Natural 20.

02:25:52.665 --> 02:26:02.327
(cheering)

02:26:02.327 --> 02:26:08.983
MATT: The Plank King gives you this very severe
look. His eyes narrowed and glancing you up and

02:26:09.056 --> 02:26:17.400
down, almost piercing you with but a glance. He
raises his hand with a grin and goes, "Oh. What's

02:26:17.400 --> 02:26:19.683
"necessary for such a thing?"

02:26:19.683 --> 02:26:21.675
TRAVIS: (whispering) Who has that shit?

02:26:21.675 --> 02:26:24.403
MARISHA: I do and Jester does.

02:26:24.403 --> 02:26:25.919
TRAVIS: You do?

02:26:25.919 --> 02:26:31.072
MARISHA: Yeah. It takes me literally punching the
shit out of Avantika though.

02:26:32.405 --> 02:26:40.366
TRAVIS: Honorable Plank King, the means justify
the ends. My compatriot here will place her Cobalt

02:26:40.366 --> 02:26:45.427
knuckles upon the chin of Avantika and you will
hear the truth. You need but only ask your

02:26:45.427 --> 02:26:48.317
questions again.

02:26:48.317 --> 02:26:55.155
MATT: "Be my guest." Avantika is like, "What
is--"

02:26:55.155 --> 02:26:56.632
MARISHA: Before she-- (double punch)

02:26:56.632 --> 02:26:59.826
(laughter)

02:26:59.826 --> 02:27:03.926
MATT: She's manacled and being held by two guards
from behind. It's auto-hit.

02:27:03.926 --> 02:27:04.995
LIAM: Holy shit.

02:27:04.995 --> 02:27:06.618
MARISHA: Go for the temple.

02:27:06.618 --> 02:27:08.066
MATT: Do you have a ki point left?

02:27:08.066 --> 02:27:13.536
MARISHA: Yeah, I have all of my ki points left.
More or less. All but one. Yep.

02:27:13.536 --> 02:27:17.088
MATT: All right. What's the DC on that?

02:27:17.088 --> 02:27:23.942
MARISHA: Mine, I'm assuming, which is 14. Hang on.
Features and traits.

02:27:23.942 --> 02:27:26.475
MATT: Yeah, whatever your DC is for all of your
monk stuff.

02:27:26.475 --> 02:27:29.292
LIAM, SAM, and TRAVIS: (whispering) Monk stuff!

02:27:29.292 --> 02:27:30.659
MARISHA: Yeah, 14.

02:27:30.659 --> 02:27:45.576
MATT: Okay. It's a wisdom save. No. That's a
natural eight plus four. 12. So all these

02:27:45.576 --> 02:27:50.177
different hits and pressure points are hit, like
under the chin, that area. Another to the sternum

02:27:50.177 --> 02:27:55.639
and another that clocks the temple. And Avantika
just, "Ugh!" (heavy breathing)

02:27:55.639 --> 02:28:02.326
MARISHA: They are unable to speak a deliberate lie
for one minute and all charisma checks have advantage.

02:28:02.326 --> 02:28:05.855
MATT: Intimidation checks? Oh, charisma checks!
Yeah, persuasion, everything else. That's right, yeah.

02:28:05.855 --> 02:28:08.773
LIAM: <i>Mein Gott.</i>

02:28:08.773 --> 02:28:13.002
TRAVIS: Make sure you tell the Plank King it's a
limited time engagement.

02:28:13.002 --> 02:28:14.384
MATT: She's like: "Ugh!"

02:28:14.384 --> 02:28:19.197
MARISHA: You have 60 seconds, but I have more
knuckles.

02:28:19.197 --> 02:28:29.117
MATT: The Plank King steps forward. "Avantika, is
what they're saying true?" She goes, (frustrated

02:28:29.117 --> 02:28:41.508
grunt) Glances aside. Doesn't respond. He leans
forward closer. "Tell me."

02:28:41.508 --> 02:28:44.691
LIAM: (whispering) Silence speaks volumes,
though.

02:28:44.691 --> 02:28:51.295
MATT: "Is what they're saying true? Is that book
containing passages where you're looking to take

02:28:51.295 --> 02:29:02.210
"this island for yourself?" Her eyes look away. She
just looks down at the rest of the dock. He leans

02:29:02.210 --> 02:29:08.075
in real close, pushing his forehead almost to
hers. "Look me in the eye, woman."

02:29:08.075 --> 02:29:11.210
MARISHA: Oh my god!

02:29:16.031 --> 02:29:35.239
MATT: She just doesn't meet his gaze. "Hmm. By the
power of The Revelry that surrounds me, let this

02:29:35.239 --> 02:29:47.405
"be a lesson to those who would work against the
words we swore to each other on this land. May

02:29:47.405 --> 02:29:56.651
"your memory be besmirched for the few days it's
recalled." He reaches forward and grabs Avantika

02:29:56.651 --> 02:30:00.819
by the throat and lifts her up and she's fighting
against it. He lifts her and looks at her. "I hope

02:30:00.819 --> 02:30:07.738
"your sea god, whatever it is, is very merciful on
the other side." (cracking) He breaks her neck

02:30:07.738 --> 02:30:17.387
with one hand. Her body goes limp in his grasp and
he throws it to the docks. "Don't worry about the

02:30:17.387 --> 02:30:26.731
"cipher." Solon goes, "It's actually quite
interesting. I'd like to continue." "Fine."

02:30:26.731 --> 02:30:29.937
LIAM: I worked through the night on that. It's
very interesting.

02:30:29.937 --> 02:30:34.343
MATT: "And it's really well done! I'm honestly
very taken aback by it. Your penmanship is quite

02:30:34.343 --> 02:30:35.422
"good as well."

02:30:35.422 --> 02:30:36.066
LIAM: Breakfast.

02:30:36.066 --> 02:30:38.850
SAM: I have a sample of her penmanship here if you
want to see some more of it.

02:30:38.850 --> 02:30:45.667
MATT: "Oh, certainly!" He goes and starts taking
it. At this point, the Plank King goes, "Take her

02:30:45.667 --> 02:30:58.383
"up top. She'll be the next on the pike. As for the
rest of you, you've pulled out a conspiracy, I'll

02:30:58.383 --> 02:31:04.869
"give you that. You've also snuck your way into The
Revelry under false pretenses. You've broken our

02:31:04.869 --> 02:31:17.534
"laws within but a day of being presented with
them, in multiple ways. That's a serious offense.

02:31:17.534 --> 02:31:34.516
"So hear my judgment upon these folk. You are
hereby banished from Darktow. Take the remnants of

02:31:34.516 --> 02:31:42.522
"the Squalleater as your own. Take whatever--" He
looks over towards the rest of the crew you hired,

02:31:42.522 --> 02:31:44.586
who are like (panicked panting).

02:31:44.586 --> 02:31:46.751
TRAVIS: (laughter) Those poor fuckers!

02:31:46.751 --> 02:31:52.595
MATT: They have had a terrible few weeks here!
Except for Orly, who's sitting there, smoking a

02:31:52.595 --> 02:31:56.677
pipe, and his one eye goes.

02:31:56.677 --> 02:31:58.034
TRAVIS: Stone-cold killer.

02:31:58.034 --> 02:31:59.994
LIAM: He is so stoned.

02:31:59.994 --> 02:32:09.771
MATT: "Take the ship you've thereby damaged. Limp
your way beyond the reefs. We're going to burn the

02:32:09.771 --> 02:32:17.416
"colors of that ship. Should you ever return to the
outskirts of the Dragshallow, we won't hesitate

02:32:17.416 --> 02:32:21.742
"but sink you to the depths below."

02:32:21.742 --> 02:32:26.405
TRAVIS: That is beyond a generous sentence.

02:32:26.405 --> 02:32:33.652
MATT: "Unshackle them. This stands immediately. I
hope you have enough supplies in that boat to last

02:32:33.652 --> 02:32:35.535
"you the rest of the journey."

02:32:35.535 --> 02:32:37.011
SAM: (whispering) I don't think that we do.

02:32:37.011 --> 02:32:38.540
TALIESIN: We'll be fine.

02:32:38.540 --> 02:32:42.396
TRAVIS: We'll make do. We will leave with great
haste.

02:32:42.396 --> 02:32:50.238
MATT: "Good. Tell the Archives that the Plank King
sends his regards."

02:32:50.238 --> 02:32:54.211
MARISHA: Will do, good sir.

02:32:54.211 --> 02:32:56.426
MATT: "Now fucking go!"

02:32:56.426 --> 02:33:00.218
LAURA: Before everybody gets on the boat, can I
run over to the docks because I'm not shackled,

02:33:00.218 --> 02:33:04.674
and I try to find the jewels that I dumped off the
docks.

02:33:04.674 --> 02:33:06.677
MATT: Okay. You have to dive into the water to do
so.

02:33:06.677 --> 02:33:07.871
LAURA: Okay.

02:33:07.871 --> 02:33:13.657
MATT: So, you jump into the water. Make an
investigation-- No, this'll be a perception check

02:33:13.657 --> 02:33:15.883
with disa-fucking-vantage.

02:33:15.883 --> 02:33:17.762
SAM: Disa-fucking-vantage!

02:33:17.762 --> 02:33:18.474
MATT: Yeah.

02:33:18.474 --> 02:33:20.302
LAURA: Ooh! (laughter)

02:33:20.302 --> 02:33:22.750
TALIESIN: Wow, fuck you!

02:33:22.750 --> 02:33:24.743
LAURA: Two ones!

02:33:24.743 --> 02:33:28.473
LIAM: You counterbalanced the rest of this game!

02:33:28.473 --> 02:33:31.765
TALIESIN: Fucking belly flop into the water!

02:33:31.765 --> 02:33:33.359
TRAVIS: Sin eater!

02:33:33.359 --> 02:33:36.307
SAM: Two ones in a roll.

02:33:36.307 --> 02:33:39.728
LIAM: Has that happened since the walk of shame?

02:33:39.728 --> 02:33:41.014
LAURA: No.

02:33:41.014 --> 02:33:44.389
LIAM: Two years ago.

02:33:44.389 --> 02:33:52.561
MATT: You spend the next five or so minutes
scrounging through silt and muck and barnacles and

02:33:52.561 --> 02:33:59.776
gathered bits of kelp and various other underwater
plant life that has rooted itself among the rocks

02:33:59.776 --> 02:34:05.672
here. You've scraped your fingers, they're
bleeding from digging through. You find a cluster

02:34:05.672 --> 02:34:10.688
of these gems that you dropped and you climb up
out of the freezing water and find one of the

02:34:10.688 --> 02:34:15.731
nearby ladders and come up. Looking at your
quarry, it is a bunch of rocks.

02:34:15.731 --> 02:34:19.234
TALIESIN: Come on, Jester, let's--

02:34:19.234 --> 02:34:21.277
MATT: Oh you don't see Jester. You just see an old
prospector come up.

02:34:21.277 --> 02:34:22.062
TALIESIN: That's right.

02:34:22.062 --> 02:34:23.825
TRAVIS: You're a prospector!

02:34:23.825 --> 02:34:28.363
LAURA: These are beautiful rocks. Beautiful.

02:34:28.363 --> 02:34:32.725
MATT: You guys are ushered to the Squalleater.
Your crew is ushered to the Squalleater.

02:34:32.725 --> 02:34:35.397
SAM: Oh! The Mist is gone? The Mistake?

02:34:35.397 --> 02:34:39.248
MATT: The Mistake is still in repairs and at this
point has been left behind.

02:34:39.248 --> 02:34:42.007
LIAM: <i>Ja,</i> we will take the bigger boat!

02:34:42.007 --> 02:34:46.891
TRAVIS: Avantika's crew are still manacled up?

02:34:46.891 --> 02:34:53.651
MATT: The remained of them, yes. Bouldergut is
heavily manacled and is currently guarded by seven

02:34:53.651 --> 02:34:54.871
different guards.

02:34:54.871 --> 02:34:56.017
MARISHA: Should we try to take them?

02:34:56.017 --> 02:34:58.193
TRAVIS: No. Maybe one or two of them. Ipess?

02:34:58.193 --> 02:35:00.072
LAURA: What? They're going to hate us.

02:35:00.072 --> 02:35:01.017
LIAM: No.

02:35:01.017 --> 02:35:03.053
TRAVIS: What? We've got to have somebody to kill
while we're at sea.

02:35:03.053 --> 02:35:03.957
LIAM: No.

02:35:03.957 --> 02:35:04.986
SAM: Yeah, we have our crew.

02:35:04.986 --> 02:35:06.545
LIAM: We have our crew. We do not need them.

02:35:06.545 --> 02:35:08.383
TALIESIN: Yeah, we've got a way.

02:35:08.383 --> 02:35:10.219
MARISHA: Yeah, we know how to sail now.

02:35:10.219 --> 02:35:12.329
TRAVIS: Better. Yeah, and they do.

02:35:12.329 --> 02:35:21.650
MATT: All right. As you guys get on the ship with
your crew, the ship is damaged, the sails are

02:35:21.650 --> 02:35:27.563
damaged, one of the masts is damaged. It's going
to need some repairs for it to be fully

02:35:27.563 --> 02:35:30.035
functional. But you have to leave now.

02:35:30.035 --> 02:35:32.132
MARISHA: Yeah, let's go.

02:35:32.132 --> 02:35:39.508
MATT: You take your positions at the ship, pull up
the anchor, and make your way limping through the

02:35:39.508 --> 02:35:47.134
channel of Dragshallow Reef, back out towards the
Swavain Islands, the Lucidian Ocean. As you slowly

02:35:47.134 --> 02:35:52.001
make your way with what little bit of wind you can
pick up to bring you out there-- some of the sails

02:35:52.001 --> 02:35:59.400
are still working, so you're not fully damaged,
but you're not optimal. There are a series of

02:35:59.400 --> 02:36:10.106
these-- what are referred to as the War Posts that
are the clusters of driftwood and these towers

02:36:10.106 --> 02:36:13.742
that are set up along the reef and on top of the
various reefs that are shallow or breach the

02:36:13.742 --> 02:36:21.860
actual surface that have cannons attached, that
have flares set up and beacons that can be lit to

02:36:21.860 --> 02:36:27.299
alert Darktow. You get a better look this time of
the system they have to defend this island from

02:36:27.299 --> 02:36:35.730
the Clovis Concord and anybody else that would
look to make their way via ship to this island.

02:36:35.730 --> 02:36:41.568
You can see them at the ready, keeping a very
close eye on your exit as you slowly walk of shame

02:36:41.568 --> 02:36:50.640
yourselves out of the purview of the Plank King
and to a very carefully earned freedom.

02:36:50.640 --> 02:36:56.133
TRAVIS: If I may, who is really good at finding
shit? You two, and anyone--

02:36:56.133 --> 02:36:57.255
MARISHA: Like investigation style?

02:36:57.255 --> 02:37:02.344
TRAVIS: Yeah. How about you three, into Avantika's
quarters and turn it upside down.

02:37:02.344 --> 02:37:06.140
MARISHA: Ooh, you are turning me on right now.

02:37:06.140 --> 02:37:07.396
TRAVIS: Not my intention, but go ahead.

02:37:07.396 --> 02:37:08.017
MARISHA: Yes!

02:37:08.017 --> 02:37:08.692
TRAVIS: Okay.

02:37:08.692 --> 02:37:15.041
TRAVIS: Just in case she booby trapped this ship,
search the hull, search her quarters, search everything.

02:37:15.041 --> 02:37:17.306
MARISHA: Yeah, check for traps first, okay?

02:37:17.306 --> 02:37:18.904
LIAM: I'll be doing that at disadvantage.

02:37:18.904 --> 02:37:20.179
TALIESIN: I'm going to try and calm the crew a
little bit.

02:37:20.179 --> 02:37:20.819
MATT: Okay.

02:37:20.819 --> 02:37:27.299
TALIESIN: I'll point out that we're-- this is all
good. We got away from the pirates, everything's all right.

02:37:27.299 --> 02:37:33.088
MATT: Make a general persuasion check for me. Just
a persuasion check.

02:37:34.587 --> 02:37:35.883
TALIESIN: That's 15.

02:37:35.883 --> 02:37:42.336
MATT: Okay, you do. A number of the crew that you
hired, some of them look like they're a little

02:37:42.360 --> 02:37:48.146
scarred from the experience, but you managed to
calm them down. They seem very thankful that

02:37:48.306 --> 02:37:51.935
you've pulled them-- you brought them into this
mess, but you pulled them out of it and there's

02:37:51.935 --> 02:37:59.557
something to that. Some of them begin to get back
to work, begin to repair some of the aspects of

02:37:59.557 --> 02:38:05.099
the ship. Man.

02:38:05.099 --> 02:38:07.985
TRAVIS: Is Jester able to mend some of those
damaged--?

02:38:07.985 --> 02:38:12.114
LAURA: That's what I was going to try to do, yeah.
Anything that's small enough, I'm going to try to

02:38:12.114 --> 02:38:13.779
mend. Small holes.

02:38:13.779 --> 02:38:14.791
LIAM: 20 percent of the damage?

02:38:14.791 --> 02:38:15.627
LAURA: Yeah.

02:38:15.627 --> 02:38:20.357
MATT: There are a few places, but for the most
part-- and it's only the one mast. You still have

02:38:20.357 --> 02:38:25.356
enough sails because it's a three-mast ship. You
can still coast the winds, but it's not going to

02:38:25.356 --> 02:38:30.733
be optimal speed. You'll have to get back to some
sort of a port to get the rest of the sails

02:38:30.733 --> 02:38:36.791
repaired because you don't have replacement sails.
The downside of the Fireball. The Fireball and

02:38:36.791 --> 02:38:41.206
the-- actually. It was a 20-foot tall Wall of
Fire.

02:38:41.206 --> 02:38:43.122
LIAM: Yes, but the upside was so--

02:38:43.122 --> 02:38:44.363
MATT: It was.

02:38:44.363 --> 02:38:46.520
SAM: Then you singed the other sails, too.

02:38:46.520 --> 02:38:48.039
MATT: Yeah, there's a lot of sail-- you have--

02:38:48.039 --> 02:38:52.821
LIAM: Yeah, 20 feet tall. For six to 12 seconds.
That didn't last more than two rounds.

02:38:52.821 --> 02:38:54.699
MATT: I know, but that's a very intense--

02:38:54.699 --> 02:38:55.771
LIAM: Absolutely.

02:38:55.771 --> 02:39:02.464
MATT: I would say comparatively, you're limping on
one full mast of functionality, and the rest of

02:39:02.464 --> 02:39:04.199
the sails are partially damaged.

02:39:04.199 --> 02:39:06.414
LIAM: (gasps) (pigeon coos) Paint on the mast.

02:39:06.414 --> 02:39:11.058
LAURA: (pigeon coo) I was thinking about it, but
it's a lot of the use of the paint because--

02:39:11.058 --> 02:39:13.364
SAM: (pigeon coo) How about a few sails?

02:39:13.364 --> 02:39:20.529
TALIESIN: We don't have to pigeon this. I mean, we
know what you can do, so maybe paint the fix for it.

02:39:20.529 --> 02:39:21.994
MATT: Just so you know--

02:39:21.994 --> 02:39:24.309
LAURA: That's what I want. I don't want to paint
the whole thing.

02:39:24.309 --> 02:39:31.048
MATT: Just so you know, this ship travels on an
average pace of around 48 miles a day. Right now

02:39:31.048 --> 02:39:35.672
with the damage the sails have sustained, you're
close to 20. You're less than half speed on the

02:39:35.672 --> 02:39:43.206
ship with the damage it's sustained at the sails.
It's going to take you a while to get anywhere.

02:39:43.206 --> 02:39:44.699
But you have it.

02:39:44.699 --> 02:39:47.617
LAURA: How big are the holes? Are they giant?

02:39:47.617 --> 02:39:48.716
MATT: They're beyond Mending.

02:39:48.716 --> 02:39:49.409
LAURA: Okay.

02:39:49.409 --> 02:39:51.178
MATT: Mending can do little tears and things.

02:39:51.178 --> 02:39:54.379
LAURA: No, I'm not talking Mending, I'm talking
how big are the holes?

02:39:54.379 --> 02:39:59.749
MATT: For the ones that are damaged, the sails are
mostly destroyed. They caught fire and burned.

02:39:59.749 --> 02:40:08.246
LIAM: I have a question. If I finally go to bed
for like 14 hours-- Minor Alchemy for a

02:40:08.246 --> 02:40:14.093
transmutation wizard. I am able to perform an
alchemical procedure on one object composed

02:40:14.093 --> 02:40:20.383
entirely of wood, stone, iron, copper, silver, and
transform it into another material. If there was

02:40:20.383 --> 02:40:25.369
damage to the mast, would I be able to shove other
things in there and turn it to wood? That seems

02:40:25.369 --> 02:40:27.872
like too much.

02:40:27.872 --> 02:40:29.956
MATT: Doesn't quite work that way, and it's
temporary. It's more--

02:40:29.956 --> 02:40:33.850
LIAM: It's a spell that I could've done, but I
didn't take that spell. I chose Counterspell.

02:40:33.850 --> 02:40:37.175
MATT: To be fair, I think that worked in your
favor. If tonight has proved anything, if the end

02:40:37.175 --> 02:40:40.317
of the last campaign has proved anything,
Counterspell's always a good choice.

02:40:40.317 --> 02:40:43.736
TALIESIN: We're going to spend a day moving
slowly, but I think we're going to slowly figure

02:40:43.736 --> 02:40:49.953
out how, between all of us, we can repair this,
and I'm sure we can figure out where to get some cloth.

02:40:49.953 --> 02:40:52.505
MARISHA: This just turned into a resource
management game.

02:40:52.505 --> 02:40:53.990
TALIESIN: Yeah, it's a lot different kind of
game.

02:40:53.990 --> 02:40:59.236
MATT: You guys have now pushed into the rest of
the seafaring mist. It takes you a while to move

02:40:59.236 --> 02:41:03.306
beyond the Dragshallow Reef, the better part of
the day before you escape the channel at the pace

02:41:03.306 --> 02:41:09.395
you're moving. The clouds are pretty heavy now.
The open sky that you enjoyed on your way to

02:41:09.395 --> 02:41:16.112
Darktow has now become-- not a storm front by any
means, but definitely cloudier skies. As you're

02:41:16.112 --> 02:41:23.654
heading outside, you can see Yasha smelling the
air and be like, "This might be getting close to

02:41:23.654 --> 02:41:26.340
"storm weather."

02:41:26.340 --> 02:41:27.693
TRAVIS: Is that a good thing?

02:41:27.693 --> 02:41:29.022
MATT: She smiles.

02:41:29.022 --> 02:41:32.168
TRAVIS: It's a good thing.

02:41:32.168 --> 02:41:37.257
MATT: Continuing past into that space, repairs are
being done best you can, with the ship still

02:41:37.257 --> 02:41:41.787
limping along. You make your way out of the
Dragshallow Reef, out into open waters, and the

02:41:41.787 --> 02:41:43.457
ocean is yours.

02:41:43.457 --> 02:41:45.159
TRAVIS: Can I find Orly?

02:41:45.159 --> 02:41:45.873
MATT: Yeah.

02:41:45.873 --> 02:41:48.431
TRAVIS: I'll bring out the map.

02:41:48.431 --> 02:41:51.111
MATT: Bring out the map.

02:41:51.111 --> 02:41:52.575
TRAVIS: I don't have it near me.

02:41:52.575 --> 02:41:53.806
LAURA: Should we get close to a port or
something?

02:41:53.806 --> 02:41:54.879
TALIESIN: Or an island where we--

02:41:54.879 --> 02:41:56.953
TRAVIS: Do we know where the map is, please?

02:41:56.953 --> 02:41:58.675
SAM: (singing) Bring out the map!

02:41:58.675 --> 02:42:04.015
MATT: It's usually right there. It got moved for
Honey Heist, that's why. Oh, is it down there? Oh,

02:42:04.015 --> 02:42:06.623
there it is! It got hidden! It got moved from me!

02:42:06.623 --> 02:42:07.310
TRAVIS: Damn it, Bobby!

02:42:07.310 --> 02:42:09.335
MATT: Damn it, Bobby. There you go.

02:42:09.335 --> 02:42:12.132
LIAM: I sell falchions and--

02:42:12.132 --> 02:42:16.664
MARISHA: I'm having an adrenaline crash now.

02:42:16.664 --> 02:42:18.528
LIAM: Yeah, we survived and--

02:42:18.528 --> 02:42:21.541
MARISHA: Are those little zoomy magnifying
glasses?

02:42:21.541 --> 02:42:23.841
LIAM: They're magnifying, Matt? Where'd you get
those?

02:42:23.841 --> 02:42:28.398
MARISHA: The crew got them. That was Max. Thanks,
producer Max!

02:42:28.398 --> 02:42:32.070
TRAVIS: Do we know if we are making our way--?

02:42:32.070 --> 02:42:35.836
MATT: You guys have just managed to make your way
out of here.

02:42:35.836 --> 02:42:37.899
SAM: Oh, going the wrong way.

02:42:37.899 --> 02:42:41.409
LIAM: So we're going right into her vagina.

02:42:41.409 --> 02:42:44.943
MATT: Well, that is the Wildmother. She is nature,
I guess.

02:42:44.943 --> 02:42:51.563
TRAVIS: I'll tell Orly: Orly, if you could help us
plot a course, as damaged as we are, heading north

02:42:51.563 --> 02:42:54.114
to this point.

02:42:54.114 --> 02:42:56.793
LAURA: Shouldn't we get to a port or something
before we--?

02:42:56.793 --> 02:42:57.892
SAM: Yeah, we need to repair first.

02:42:57.892 --> 02:42:58.916
LIAM: There ain't no fucking port around here,
motherfucker.

02:42:58.916 --> 02:43:04.936
SAM: Well, maybe there's something over here! He
knows about something. Let's ask! Orly? M-m-maybe?

02:43:04.936 --> 02:43:06.969
TRAVIS: Wow.

02:43:06.969 --> 02:43:14.902
LIAM: Max Headroom, coming at you from the
mid-80s! W-w-what?

02:43:14.902 --> 02:43:17.886
MATT: It's a good thing I grew up a stutterer.

02:43:17.886 --> 02:43:23.572
LIAM: Yeah. Matt is just barely old enough to know
what that is.

02:43:23.572 --> 02:43:25.103
MATT: Oh, I know Max Headroom.

02:43:25.103 --> 02:43:28.307
LIAM: I said you know what it is! Just barely.

02:43:28.307 --> 02:43:32.271
MATT: It's funny, I didn't realize who played him
until years later and I was like, really, him?

02:43:32.271 --> 02:43:33.730
TRAVIS: Wait, who played him?

02:43:33.730 --> 02:43:35.334
MATT: Oh, what's the actor?

02:43:35.334 --> 02:43:39.204
LIAM: He was in The Stand as the Trashcan Man.

02:43:39.204 --> 02:43:45.333
MATT: He was, and he played the part of Jobe in
Lawnmower Man 2. Anyway!

02:43:45.333 --> 02:43:55.193
TRAVIS: Because this is on a trade run, and this
whole isle is part of that, could we make port for

02:43:55.193 --> 02:43:57.595
more extensive repairs there?

02:43:57.595 --> 02:44:01.857
MATT: It's a resource stop. It might have some
repairs, in your experience. It's not a major port

02:44:01.857 --> 02:44:05.563
by any means, it's more of a small--

02:44:05.563 --> 02:44:06.537
TRAVIS: Resupply?

02:44:06.537 --> 02:44:07.374
MATT: Yeah, it's a resupply.

02:44:07.374 --> 02:44:08.794
LAURA: Might have canvas, at least.

02:44:08.794 --> 02:44:10.368
TALIESIN: We can use Divination.

02:44:10.368 --> 02:44:11.474
TRAVIS: That's the closest thing.

02:44:11.474 --> 02:44:12.813
MATT: From your experience--

02:44:12.813 --> 02:44:15.417
TRAVIS: Divination? What do you mean?

02:44:15.417 --> 02:44:21.140
TALIESIN: If it's been 24 hours-- once I have a
long rest, I can take my morning meditation and

02:44:21.140 --> 02:44:27.002
ask the Wildmother if there's a place of calm for
our boat.

02:44:27.002 --> 02:44:28.463
LAURA: You can do that?

02:44:28.463 --> 02:44:29.425
TALIESIN: I can do a lot of stuff, man.

02:44:29.425 --> 02:44:31.643
TRAVIS: I would love to have you do that.

02:44:31.643 --> 02:44:33.349
LIAM: Are you doing that?

02:44:33.349 --> 02:44:36.744
TALIESIN: I was going to do that. Yeah.

02:44:36.744 --> 02:44:45.127
MATT: To answer your question, Orly goes, "Yeah.
There's a way to get that working for you. We'll

02:44:45.127 --> 02:44:58.357
"all take course and head for that m-m-mighty
dangerous part of the sea." He marks it and they

02:44:58.357 --> 02:45:02.285
set it. You guys have been making your way around
the Dragshallow northward towards that area.

02:45:02.285 --> 02:45:04.419
SAM: Is that past where we're going?

02:45:04.570 --> 02:45:06.572
TRAVIS: It is, but we don't have any other--

02:45:06.572 --> 02:45:10.048
TALIESIN: Yeah, in the early morning I'm going to
go to the crow's nest and have a ten-minute

02:45:10.048 --> 02:45:17.103
meditation and ask the Wildmother which direction
we should be heading to find some safe harbor to

02:45:17.103 --> 02:45:20.343
heal ourselves and heal our boat.

02:45:20.343 --> 02:45:22.521
MATT: Okay. Is this an ability, or--

02:45:22.521 --> 02:45:25.561
TALIESIN: Yes, it is a 4th-level spell, it's
Divination.

02:45:25.561 --> 02:45:27.144
MATT: Oh, there we go.

02:45:27.144 --> 02:45:34.692
TALIESIN: I'm using it. It takes ten minutes, and
you can be as obtuse as you like. You can be a

02:45:34.692 --> 02:45:37.695
bird that flies in a direction, an insect, or
whatever.

02:45:37.695 --> 02:45:40.725
TRAVIS: Thank you for the Shawshank obtuse
reference.

02:45:40.725 --> 02:45:50.960
MATT: Okay, yeah. The Wildmother responds--
Actually, let me see what will be the best answer

02:45:50.960 --> 02:46:01.709
to this one, give me just a second. (stage
whisper) Talk amongst yourselves.

02:46:01.709 --> 02:46:08.281
TALIESIN: I was seeing if there was anything else
I can do-- I'm setting day two spells so we'll

02:46:08.281 --> 02:46:09.649
have food and water.

02:46:09.649 --> 02:46:15.819
LIAM: If we're talking about, like business shit,
Caleb is going to Beau and saying: I'm sorry, I

02:46:15.819 --> 02:46:21.561
know that this has been less than ten days, but I
need my cat, so I am taking my owl, I apologize.

02:46:21.561 --> 02:46:35.420
On a side note, so impressed. I walk off with my
little tiny one-ounce owl.

02:46:35.420 --> 02:46:36.466
MARISHA: Bye, Frumpkin.

02:46:36.466 --> 02:46:41.884
LIAM: I will take the time to turn Frumpkin- I
have two uses left with incense- back into a

02:46:41.884 --> 02:46:49.558
Bengal cat. So he can live his best life as a
Bengal cat.

02:46:49.558 --> 02:46:52.128
SAM: (imitating Liam's accent) Bengal cat.

02:46:52.128 --> 02:46:54.766
LIAM: Diplomatic cat-munity.

02:47:05.303 --> 02:47:11.255
MATT: You get that situated. Anybody else doing
anything?

02:47:11.255 --> 02:47:13.100
LAURA: I'm going to--

02:47:13.100 --> 02:47:22.943
MATT: Your answer, by the way, is: "Bisaft Isle
brings you safest harbor in what you seek."

02:47:22.943 --> 02:47:26.673
TALIESIN and SAM: Bisaft.

02:47:26.673 --> 02:47:35.325
MATT: There's a warm, gentle embrace that comes
with the words, an understanding, and a familiar

02:47:35.325 --> 02:47:44.638
matronly guidance that brings you calm on the
ocean seas that have long brought you anxiety. For

02:47:44.638 --> 02:47:48.534
the first time in probably a good number of weeks,
you get to walk out on that deck, take a deep

02:47:48.534 --> 02:47:53.309
breath of ocean air, and feel really confident.

02:47:53.309 --> 02:48:03.420
TALIESIN: Sea smells different today. Might just
be the charred boat and-- Oh, no. Bisaft.

02:48:03.420 --> 02:48:05.587
TRAVIS: You look rejuvenated. Did you say Bisaft?

02:48:05.587 --> 02:48:10.833
TALIESIN: Bisaft. We're to head towards Bisaft.

02:48:10.833 --> 02:48:12.694
TRAVIS: You're sure?

02:48:12.694 --> 02:48:15.137
TALIESIN: Sure as anything.

02:48:15.137 --> 02:48:17.680
TRAVIS: All right then. You can let Orly know.

02:48:17.680 --> 02:48:19.671
TALIESIN: Orly!

02:48:19.671 --> 02:48:22.530
MATT: "Mm-hmm?"

02:48:22.530 --> 02:48:24.150
TALIESIN: Know the Isle of Bisaft?

02:48:24.150 --> 02:48:26.893
MATT: "Oh, I'm quite familiar."

02:48:26.893 --> 02:48:30.928
TALIESIN: That seem to be the direction we're
heading right now?

02:48:30.928 --> 02:48:37.936
MATT: "About as close as any direction gets,
really." Other eye, even.

02:48:37.936 --> 02:48:41.987
TALIESIN: I think that might be the place we ought
to go.

02:48:42.487 --> 02:48:53.699
MATT: Making it jump around a bit, guys. "Mm. Very
well. M-m-make sure to point this ship in that direction."

02:48:53.699 --> 02:48:54.835
TALIESIN: Thank you.

02:48:54.835 --> 02:48:56.925
MATT: "And you."

02:48:57.802 --> 02:49:03.511
SAM: On the first day we were on this boat, me and
Beau and others were going to go into Avantika's

02:49:03.511 --> 02:49:05.273
cabin and snoop around.

02:49:05.273 --> 02:49:11.534
LIAM: Oh right. I rolled an 18 and a 19 ten
minutes ago.

02:49:11.534 --> 02:49:15.171
MARISHA: I don't know if I rolled. I don't think I
did.

02:49:15.171 --> 02:49:19.535
SAM: I didn't roll yet either, but I was going to
crawl in through the hole in her floor if it's

02:49:19.535 --> 02:49:20.735
still there.

02:49:20.735 --> 02:49:21.767
MATT: Oh, it's still there.

02:49:21.767 --> 02:49:27.763
SAM: To avoid any traps, and then look around the
door from the inside to see if she had trapped it

02:49:27.763 --> 02:49:29.266
or anything.

02:49:29.266 --> 02:49:32.078
MATT: Okay. Make an investigation check on that.

02:49:33.239 --> 02:49:35.472
SAM: 20. 19.

02:49:35.472 --> 02:49:36.679
MATT: No, it is not trapped.

02:49:36.679 --> 02:49:38.612
SAM: I'll open it and let you guys in.

02:49:38.612 --> 02:49:48.290
LIAM: I rolled an investigation check ten minutes
ago at disadvantage and the lower is a 27. My

02:49:48.290 --> 02:49:50.896
investigation is plus eight. I'm smart--

02:49:50.896 --> 02:49:52.041
MATT: The lower was 19?

02:49:52.041 --> 02:49:54.569
LIAM: Yes. I rolled an 18 and a 19.

02:49:54.569 --> 02:49:58.255
SAM: Well, I'll show Caleb around the room that
I've already been in to see if he can find

02:49:58.255 --> 02:49:59.941
anything else.

02:49:59.941 --> 02:50:03.267
MARISHA: I'm in there too.

02:50:03.267 --> 02:50:12.341
MATT: Glancing around, you find-- There's her
dresser with a number of outfits, coats, shirts,

02:50:12.341 --> 02:50:19.192
things that belong to the captain that you guys
get to distribute as you see fit.

02:50:19.192 --> 02:50:21.428
LAURA: (cartoon voice) Hey, look at me! I'm
Avantika!

02:50:21.428 --> 02:50:23.473
LIAM: Are there any more gigantic hats?

02:50:23.473 --> 02:50:25.490
MARISHA: I was going to say teddies, but...

02:50:25.490 --> 02:50:26.800
MATT: There's a few hats, yeah.

02:50:26.800 --> 02:50:28.176
LIAM: Gigantic hats.

02:50:28.176 --> 02:50:29.287
MATT: Avantika-sized hats.

02:50:29.287 --> 02:50:33.553
MARISHA and TALIESIN: (singing) Hats and teddies.
Hats, hats, and teddies.

02:50:33.553 --> 02:50:40.001
(laughter)

02:50:40.001 --> 02:50:45.199
SAM: Does she have a fragrance or anything? Like a
perfume?

02:50:45.199 --> 02:50:47.157
MARISHA: Chanel No. 5.

02:50:47.157 --> 02:50:52.352
MATT: I will say you do find some scented oils,
but that's the extent.

02:50:52.352 --> 02:50:53.428
SAM: I'll take those.

02:50:53.428 --> 02:50:55.213
MATT: She's not a perfume keeper.

02:50:55.213 --> 02:50:57.452
TALIESIN: How about that statue above the door?

02:50:57.452 --> 02:50:59.784
LAURA: Yeah, her little altar.

02:50:59.784 --> 02:51:02.822
MATT: The altar is still there, the altar to
Uk'otoa.

02:51:02.822 --> 02:51:07.891
MARISHA: The maps-- the stuff behind her, charting
out where she was going, anything in there?

02:51:07.891 --> 02:51:17.922
MATT: Yeah. You find a few other maps and things
that refer to a-- You see it breaking down the

02:51:17.922 --> 02:51:22.124
different trade routes, and you see other paths
breaking out; those that try and avoid the trade

02:51:22.124 --> 02:51:26.051
routes to avoid the pirates. Those different paths
they might take at different times of the year to

02:51:26.051 --> 02:51:30.566
try and head off people that are trying to avoid
the waters that they're looking in. You find maps

02:51:30.566 --> 02:51:38.500
that deal with the path to Urukayxl, and you see
the handwritten map by Jamedi that was the path

02:51:38.500 --> 02:51:45.309
you guys were lead through on Urukayxl to find the
temple. You find another map that has circled

02:51:45.309 --> 02:51:53.827
heavily the archipelago that you've already sussed
out, and you find recent notes on that same map

02:51:53.827 --> 02:52:00.239
that refer to the loose area circled where your
ship went down that time ago.

02:52:00.308 --> 02:52:06.155
TRAVIS: Will we pass over that area as we're
heading towards Bisaft?

02:52:06.155 --> 02:52:13.584
MATT: Well, you'll get near that area. If you want
to head that way, you can let Orly know to--

02:52:13.584 --> 02:52:15.020
MARISHA: It's on the way...

02:52:15.020 --> 02:52:16.473
LIAM: Are you in this room with us too, right
now?

02:52:16.473 --> 02:52:19.143
TRAVIS: No, I'm just asking.

02:52:19.143 --> 02:52:25.225
MATT: You find a lot of those materials. You get
the sense that, aside from the maps, most of the

02:52:25.225 --> 02:52:27.928
information that she had, she kept in that book.

02:52:27.928 --> 02:52:35.692
MARISHA: Any supplies list? Any inventory: canvas
on board, things to make supplies?

02:52:35.692 --> 02:52:38.387
MATT: You find a number of fine cheeses,
actually.

02:52:38.387 --> 02:52:42.614
MARISHA: Chocolate dipped strawberries,
champ-pag-nay.

02:52:42.614 --> 02:52:47.467
MATT: Not quite. All the good food was kept for
the captain and some of it's turning a little, but

02:52:47.467 --> 02:52:57.845
it's cheese. Some better treats and some sugared
candies that were kept specifically, like a

02:52:57.845 --> 02:53:00.769
private stash for the captain, you manage to
find.

02:53:00.769 --> 02:53:06.316
SAM: While we're down there, looking around, I'm
going to say: So, you know, it's just the three of

02:53:06.316 --> 02:53:08.125
us down here.

02:53:08.125 --> 02:53:09.889
LIAM: Yeah. I'm sitting on the bed right now.

02:53:09.889 --> 02:53:12.745
SAM: We have some secrets between us already.

02:53:12.745 --> 02:53:16.154
MARISHA: Yeah, it's been a while since just the
three of us have been in a room together.

02:53:16.154 --> 02:53:24.671
LIAM: Wait a second, look at me. I'm sitting on
the bed. I am the servant of a demigod. This is

02:53:24.671 --> 02:53:27.248
going to be very hard for Fjord.

02:53:27.248 --> 02:53:28.969
SAM: Yes, well...

02:53:28.969 --> 02:53:31.721
MARISHA: What? You're jumping around so much.

02:53:31.721 --> 02:53:37.355
LIAM: We can get back to what you're talking
about, but think about it for a moment; it's just

02:53:37.355 --> 02:53:45.965
the three of us, right? We have our heads in the
same game. We are the three assholes in this

02:53:45.965 --> 02:53:47.531
group, yeah?

02:53:47.531 --> 02:53:51.869
SAM: I'm asshole adjacent.

02:53:51.869 --> 02:53:53.751
MARISHA: She's quite pleasant, actually.

02:53:53.751 --> 02:53:55.025
LIAM: That is correct.

02:53:55.025 --> 02:53:57.782
MARISHA: She might be better than both of us
combined.

02:53:57.782 --> 02:54:04.541
LIAM: I'm joking because this has been such a hard
day, but Fjord is going to find this very difficult.

02:54:04.541 --> 02:54:07.391
SAM: We're going to protect him, like we always
do.

02:54:07.391 --> 02:54:12.518
MARISHA: Which part difficult? Losing his fuck
buddy? It's not that difficult.

02:54:12.518 --> 02:54:20.755
LIAM: That is minimalizing what he is dealing with
right now. He is trying to find a father, he has

02:54:20.755 --> 02:54:26.903
compromised himself with this woman for us, for
himself, for all of our safety. It is going to be

02:54:26.903 --> 02:54:28.181
difficult for him.

02:54:28.181 --> 02:54:35.080
MARISHA: Of course it's minimalizing, have you met
me? Everything I do is minimalizing.

02:54:35.080 --> 02:54:37.993
LIAM: You have your pluses and your minuses.

02:54:37.993 --> 02:54:48.302
SAM: Speaking of your pluses: the Expositors?
You're special forces, did I hear that correctly?

02:54:48.302 --> 02:54:50.293
Is that what you are called?

02:54:50.293 --> 02:54:51.204
MARISHA: Yeah.

02:54:51.204 --> 02:54:54.836
SAM: Is that true? It seemed pretty true.

02:54:54.836 --> 02:54:57.643
MARISHA: Yeah, what Caleb said.

02:54:57.643 --> 02:54:58.927
LIAM: It's mostly true.

02:54:58.927 --> 02:55:00.628
SAM: What do you mean-- How do you know?

02:55:00.628 --> 02:55:03.480
MARISHA: Yeah, how do you know?

02:55:03.480 --> 02:55:10.405
LIAM: She is too educated. She is too in-the-know
to talk the way she does, to be interested in just

02:55:10.405 --> 02:55:19.843
drinking and chasing our barbarian friend. She is
very educated. I don't know which parts are true.

02:55:19.843 --> 02:55:23.783
SAM: Well, which parts are true?

02:55:23.783 --> 02:55:25.623
MARISHA: You want to take a guess?

02:55:25.623 --> 02:55:32.878
SAM: I think you're a secret agent! I think you're
on a dangerous mission- a life or death mission-

02:55:32.878 --> 02:55:39.100
to find bad guys and take them down! To get the
collar and bring them in to the po-po, or

02:55:39.100 --> 02:55:42.642
something. I don't know how it works! I'm not a
secret agent, you are!

02:55:42.642 --> 02:55:47.155
MARISHA: It's very romanticized, but on that note:
Caleb, do you think you could recreate that cipher

02:55:47.155 --> 02:55:51.174
that you made and have one on hand?

02:55:51.237 --> 02:55:53.713
LIAM: Of course. That is easy.

02:55:53.713 --> 02:55:56.156
MARISHA: I'd like a copy, if you don't mind.

02:55:56.156 --> 02:55:59.872
LIAM: Sure, what are friends for.

02:55:59.872 --> 02:56:02.638
SAM: Do you have a license to kill?

02:56:03.689 --> 02:56:13.492
MARISHA: Got them right here, Nott. Just these--
No, that wasn't working? No? All right. Yeah, it's

02:56:13.492 --> 02:56:18.766
a little true, but not as intense as you think.

02:56:18.766 --> 02:56:20.875
SAM: Are there others like you?

02:56:20.875 --> 02:56:22.697
MARISHA: Monks?

02:56:22.697 --> 02:56:24.811
SAM: No, like--

02:56:24.811 --> 02:56:26.092
MARISHA: Expositors?

02:56:26.092 --> 02:56:27.521
SAM: Yeah, Delta Force.

02:56:27.521 --> 02:56:28.929
MARISHA: Yes.

02:56:28.929 --> 02:56:34.219
SAM: How do you know who's who? Do you have a
sign? Secret handshake?

02:56:35.690 --> 02:56:38.699
MARISHA: Kind of new to it all, to be honest.

02:56:41.721 --> 02:56:44.333
SAM: You guys are really cool.

02:56:44.333 --> 02:56:49.704
LIAM: No. I am looking forward to getting back to
the mainland, and I don't mean the Menagerie

02:56:49.704 --> 02:56:57.470
Coast. Although... We need to get Jester back to
her mother if we can, but I am not looking forward

02:56:57.470 --> 02:57:01.091
to being here anymore. I want to get back to the
Empire.

02:57:01.091 --> 02:57:08.480
MARISHA: Speaking of time that it takes to travel,
are we sure that Avantika was the only one who was

02:57:08.480 --> 02:57:12.698
interested in what Uk'otoa has to offer?

02:57:12.698 --> 02:57:19.490
LIAM: Well, there is still Vandren. I have read
every inch of her notes, I have communicated them to you.

02:57:19.490 --> 02:57:25.357
MARISHA: I guess what I'm saying is, are we still
going to be competing against others once the

02:57:25.357 --> 02:57:29.440
Plank King successfully deciphers that book?

02:57:29.440 --> 02:57:38.515
LIAM: I would imagine the Plank King would not
know what to make of it. It clearly damns her. It

02:57:38.515 --> 02:57:42.562
does not give him enough information-- He wouldn't
know what to do with it.

02:57:42.562 --> 02:57:44.409
MARISHA: It does kind of sound like a wives'
tale.

02:57:44.409 --> 02:57:50.974
LIAM: Yeah, he's not a big thinker. He is
formidable, but not a big thinker. I think we will

02:57:50.974 --> 02:57:53.851
have an easier time getting to this boat.

02:57:53.851 --> 02:57:57.811
MARISHA: Let's go talk about it with the others, I
think.

02:57:57.811 --> 02:58:02.590
SAM: Your secret is safe with me.

02:58:03.358 --> 02:58:05.958
LAURA: Above deck, can I go find Fjord?

02:58:05.958 --> 02:58:07.689
MATT: Yeah.

02:58:07.689 --> 02:58:13.572
LAURA: So... that happened. (giggles)

02:58:13.572 --> 02:58:15.573
TRAVIS: Yeah.

02:58:15.573 --> 02:58:19.278
LAURA: How do you feel about it?

02:58:19.278 --> 02:58:21.851
TRAVIS: Relieved.

02:58:21.851 --> 02:58:23.014
LAURA: Yeah?

02:58:23.014 --> 02:58:29.662
TRAVIS: Yeah. I was worried for a moment there. I
knew it was going to come to something like that,

02:58:29.662 --> 02:58:32.420
but Caleb pulling the trigger the way he did
was--

02:58:32.420 --> 02:58:35.253
LAURA: Did he cause that explosion?

02:58:35.253 --> 02:58:36.718
TRAVIS: Yeah.

02:58:36.718 --> 02:58:38.223
LAURA: Wow.

02:58:38.223 --> 02:58:39.198
TRAVIS: Right.

02:58:39.198 --> 02:58:40.908
LAURA: He did a lot of damage.

02:58:40.908 --> 02:58:45.180
TRAVIS: He did. He's very strong.

02:58:45.180 --> 02:58:52.203
LAURA: So now we're going to find the place where
your ship wrecked, yeah?

02:58:52.203 --> 02:58:55.179
TRAVIS: I think so, yeah.

02:58:55.179 --> 02:58:58.835
LAURA: You didn't get to ask them about Vandren,
though.

02:58:59.268 --> 02:59:12.120
TRAVIS: No, I didn't. It hurts to see so many
react to a name that only meant so much to me,

02:59:12.120 --> 02:59:19.036
but-- I don't even know if he's alive. We might
find him down there.

02:59:19.322 --> 02:59:28.397
LAURA: Wow. Do you think if we find him, you'll
stop talking like him?

02:59:31.178 --> 02:59:34.124
TRAVIS: We'll see.

02:59:35.619 --> 02:59:39.489
LAURA: You know, I could probably send a message
to the Plank King and ask him about Vandren, if

02:59:39.489 --> 02:59:41.341
you want me to.

02:59:41.634 --> 02:59:43.035
TRAVIS: What do you mean?

02:59:43.035 --> 02:59:47.992
LAURA: Well, I can send him a message the same way
I try to talk to my mama, and the Gentleman, and

02:59:47.992 --> 02:59:50.353
Kiri sometimes.

02:59:50.353 --> 02:59:53.223
TRAVIS: You send messages to Kiri?

02:59:53.223 --> 02:59:54.159
LAURA: Yeah.

02:59:54.159 --> 02:59:55.380
TRAVIS: What do you say?

02:59:55.380 --> 03:00:00.073
LAURA: Oh, just that she's really cute, and that I
miss her, and I wish I could see her, and I hope

03:00:00.073 --> 03:00:07.509
she's enjoying herself, and that I am sorry that
we haven't seen each other in a while, and that we

03:00:07.509 --> 03:00:09.971
are pirates, and--

03:00:09.971 --> 03:00:13.487
TRAVIS: Can she respond to these messages?

03:00:13.487 --> 03:00:22.687
LAURA: She usually responds with, "We're pirates,
and I miss you, and--"

03:00:22.687 --> 03:00:24.037
TRAVIS: (as Jester) Go fuck yourself.

03:00:24.037 --> 03:00:28.619
LAURA: No, she doesn't say that. She says, "Yes,
I'm very cute," a lot.

03:00:28.619 --> 03:00:34.481
TRAVIS: Right. I suppose, what would you put in
the letter to the Plank King?

03:00:34.481 --> 03:00:36.788
LAURA: Whatever you want me to.

03:00:36.788 --> 03:00:53.029
TRAVIS: I mean, I don't know if it's necessary. I
can't think of anything as of yet. I don't know,

03:00:53.029 --> 03:00:55.926
maybe I'll just let you know. Thank you for
offering, though.

03:00:55.926 --> 03:00:59.575
LAURA: Of course. Your teeth are coming in.

03:00:59.575 --> 03:01:02.870
TRAVIS: Yeah.

03:01:02.870 --> 03:01:07.338
LAURA: I saw it peek out of your lip just now.

03:01:07.338 --> 03:01:17.639
TRAVIS: Okay, all right. Yeah. Thank you for not
telling the others.

03:01:17.639 --> 03:01:21.491
LAURA: Of course, Fjord.

03:01:24.250 --> 03:01:26.804
TRAVIS: I've got to go check on Orly, make sure
we're going the right way.

03:01:26.804 --> 03:01:29.786
LAURA: Yeah, I'm going to go see if everything's
mended over this way.

03:01:31.743 --> 03:01:34.046
MARISHA: Mended over this way.

03:01:36.993 --> 03:01:40.041
LIAM: Put a piece of paper back together.

03:01:41.509 --> 03:01:50.194
MATT: It's going to take you about a week to get
to the location that you're seeking.

03:01:50.194 --> 03:01:52.414
MARISHA: The boat or the island?

03:01:52.414 --> 03:01:54.431
TRAVIS: The island.

03:01:54.431 --> 03:02:00.104
MATT: No, the island's going to take longer than
that-- to get to where the last time you recall

03:02:00.104 --> 03:02:01.538
your ship going down.

03:02:01.538 --> 03:02:03.748
MARISHA: With our shit all fucked up?

03:02:03.748 --> 03:02:07.677
MATT: Yeah, it would take a shorter time. It's
about eight days or so to get there, eyeballing it

03:02:07.677 --> 03:02:13.143
from here, I'd say. More than that, ten days.

03:02:13.143 --> 03:02:17.452
LAURA: Can we cast Control Water to get us there
faster at all?

03:02:17.452 --> 03:02:19.073
MATT: Do you have access to Control Water?

03:02:19.073 --> 03:02:20.268
LAURA: Of course I do.

03:02:20.268 --> 03:02:21.292
TRAVIS and LIAM: You do?

03:02:21.292 --> 03:02:22.498
MATT: Then yeah.

03:02:22.498 --> 03:02:23.713
LIAM: Oh fuck.

03:02:23.713 --> 03:02:25.362
LAURA: Maybe I can do that every day.

03:02:25.362 --> 03:02:27.641
MATT: Okay. I'll say, with the Control Water--

03:02:27.641 --> 03:02:29.352
TRAVIS: Fucking secrets.

03:02:29.352 --> 03:02:32.535
TALIESIN: I was about to say, I might be able to
do that too.

03:02:32.883 --> 03:02:37.861
SAM: Come on, everyone has Control Water, don't
they? I've got it.

03:02:37.861 --> 03:02:45.359
LIAM: I've been waiting to drop it. Fucking water
genasi heritage, man.

03:02:45.359 --> 03:02:48.667
TALIESIN: Nope, never mind-- oh, yeah, I've got
it, too.

03:02:48.667 --> 03:02:50.031
MATT: It's in the cleric list, yeah.

03:02:50.031 --> 03:02:54.912
MARISHA: It's a cleric-- oh god! d4 just went
flying!

03:02:55.860 --> 03:03:00.579
MATT: Between the two of you, it allows you a
brief moment where you can actually surge the

03:03:00.579 --> 03:03:09.821
water and grant you a speed boost. I'd say that'll
cut three days off of your travel-- the two of

03:03:09.821 --> 03:03:14.953
you, each day, spending that slot to push it. It's
like a speedboat burst. All of a sudden, your

03:03:14.953 --> 03:03:22.723
giant, three-mast ship is going (crashing water),
speedboating across the ocean briefly.

03:03:22.723 --> 03:03:28.950
MARISHA: Is it an event each day? Does the crew
come out and we all join. Like, "Yeah!"

03:03:28.950 --> 03:03:31.250
TALIESIN: It's like in Mary Poppins; everyone
holds the china.

03:03:31.250 --> 03:03:32.355
MARISHA: Exactly!

03:03:32.355 --> 03:03:33.999
TALIESIN: And 12 o'clock.

03:03:33.999 --> 03:03:35.930
MARISHA: And let's go.

03:03:35.930 --> 03:03:38.407
LIAM: You're so stupid, Rose.

03:03:38.407 --> 03:03:44.500
MATT: Eventually, you make your way to the open
waters in the vicinity of-- Orly goes with you

03:03:44.500 --> 03:03:49.500
each day and looks about and gives you the
once-over and goes, "I'm pretty sure that we're

03:03:49.500 --> 03:03:53.144
"pretty dang close to that place you were asking
about."

03:03:53.144 --> 03:03:59.161
TRAVIS: I appreciate that, Orly. Hey, Caduceus, do
you have any way of, I don't know-- you've got

03:03:59.161 --> 03:04:05.073
those vibes, right?-- feeling down and, I don't
know, doing a little ping on the bottom?

03:04:05.141 --> 03:04:08.005
TALIESIN: What do you-- I don't entirely
understand what you're--

03:04:08.005 --> 03:04:11.750
TRAVIS: I don't know, I don't want to put you in a
box or anything, but you seem to pick up the most.

03:04:11.750 --> 03:04:19.254
TALIESIN: You want to see if I get-- oh, for the
ship. I don't know. That's a--

03:04:19.728 --> 03:04:22.211
LAURA: That'd be a Locate Object sort of
situation?

03:04:22.211 --> 03:04:33.805
TALIESIN: I've got Locate Creature. Yeah, we've
both got Locate Object, so we can both help with that.

03:04:33.805 --> 03:04:35.043
SAM: What object?

03:04:35.043 --> 03:04:36.318
LAURA: A ship.

03:04:36.318 --> 03:04:42.632
TRAVIS: I'll summon the falchion and I'll say:
Maybe try to locate this, and I'll point towards

03:04:42.632 --> 03:04:47.714
the eye. Not this eye, but a similar eye.

03:04:47.714 --> 03:04:49.007
LIAM: Do you mean your penis?

03:04:49.007 --> 03:04:50.189
TRAVIS: Nope.

03:04:50.189 --> 03:04:52.122
LAURA: I'm going to do it.

03:04:52.122 --> 03:04:58.749
MATT: Okay. It's a thousand-foot range, and it has
to be something familiar to you.

03:04:58.749 --> 03:05:03.039
TALIESIN: I'm looking for a boat. I'm looking for
a ship. I'm looking for a shipwreck, not an

03:05:03.039 --> 03:05:05.100
object. We could do object, too.

03:05:05.100 --> 03:05:07.126
LAURA: Yeah, I'm going to look for his.

03:05:07.126 --> 03:05:13.805
MATT: Okay. That's 2nd-level? It lasts for ten
minutes.

03:05:13.805 --> 03:05:16.171
TALIESIN: So we can take turns.

03:05:16.171 --> 03:05:18.688
MATT: Okay, and how many spell slots do you have
2nd-level each?

03:05:18.688 --> 03:05:19.863
LAURA: Three each.

03:05:19.863 --> 03:05:30.512
MATT: So if you're both trading off, it's about
three chances per type of use per day. How many

03:05:30.512 --> 03:05:34.170
days you want to spend looking total?

03:05:34.170 --> 03:05:35.586
MARISHA: For the boat?

03:05:35.586 --> 03:05:36.600
MATT: Yeah.

03:05:36.600 --> 03:05:37.969
TRAVIS: How long do we have?

03:05:37.969 --> 03:05:39.305
MATT: It's up to you.

03:05:39.305 --> 03:05:41.300
SAM: Do we have unlimited supplies?

03:05:41.300 --> 03:05:43.579
MATT: Well, these guys can summon stuff with
magic, if I recall.

03:05:43.579 --> 03:05:49.353
TALIESIN: Yeah, so the food ain't good, but it's
edible and the water's fine.

03:05:49.353 --> 03:05:53.493
MARISHA: Until we find it.

03:05:53.493 --> 03:06:00.040
TRAVIS: Yeah? What, like two days and then go fix
the boat proper and come back if we have to?

03:06:01.021 --> 03:06:03.907
MARISHA: I don't know. Maybe that's a team
discussion.

03:06:04.329 --> 03:06:08.869
TRAVIS: How about we spend two to three days, and
if we don't find it, we can go and repair the boat

03:06:08.869 --> 03:06:11.039
proper or at least get the materials to do that?

03:06:11.039 --> 03:06:15.434
TALIESIN: We can cast it at level three also,
which is another--

03:06:15.434 --> 03:06:23.772
SAM: If we find it, though, and we go down there--
we can't go down there. Can we go down there?

03:06:23.772 --> 03:06:26.026
TRAVIS: Sure we can.

03:06:26.026 --> 03:06:28.616
SAM: But then we can't make a hasty retreat.

03:06:28.616 --> 03:06:32.420
LAURA: Yeah, it might be smart to have a boat that
actually works before we go down.

03:06:32.420 --> 03:06:34.834
SAM: I guess we could do a recon first.

03:06:34.834 --> 03:06:39.214
MARISHA: There still begs the question of, is
someone else going to come looking for this? Now

03:06:39.214 --> 03:06:40.564
that the Plank King--

03:06:40.564 --> 03:06:42.448
TALIESIN: I like that we're here now.

03:06:42.448 --> 03:06:48.610
MARISHA: We gave the book with the cipher over, so
if anybody else wants it--

03:06:48.610 --> 03:06:50.766
LAURA: Yeah, but we ripped out the page saying
where to find--

03:06:50.766 --> 03:06:55.794
MARISHA: We did! Oh my god!

03:06:55.794 --> 03:06:58.940
LIAM: All the pertinent information is also in
here.

03:06:58.940 --> 03:07:04.690
TRAVIS: Nott, I would leave it at your discretion.
We all have the ability to travel under the waves

03:07:04.690 --> 03:07:07.160
with great ease.

03:07:07.160 --> 03:07:12.093
SAM: We do? How? I don't.

03:07:12.093 --> 03:07:17.829
TRAVIS: I have a way of making it so that water
becomes like air for you down there.

03:07:17.829 --> 03:07:22.637
SAM: Does it feel like water?

03:07:22.637 --> 03:07:28.818
TRAVIS: It feels a little thicker, like if you
were in a really dense fog, maybe?

03:07:28.818 --> 03:07:30.980
SAM: But it's still water?

03:07:30.980 --> 03:07:32.474
TRAVIS: It is.

03:07:32.474 --> 03:07:38.368
LAURA: But you can breathe it, so it's really
not.

03:07:38.368 --> 03:07:42.797
TRAVIS: Or you could stay above if you wanted to
send a Message if some trouble appears on the

03:07:42.797 --> 03:07:47.390
horizon, I'd just hate to leave you behind on such
a great adventure. There could be buttons, there

03:07:47.390 --> 03:07:50.553
could be little jewels, ingots--

03:07:50.553 --> 03:07:54.912
SAM: Don't you talk down to me. I know what you're
up to.

03:07:54.912 --> 03:07:57.859
TRAVIS: What are you talking about? Iit's the
bottom of the ocean. Ships throw people all the time.

03:07:57.859 --> 03:08:01.649
LIAM: Full disclosure, I could help you cope
with--

03:08:01.649 --> 03:08:04.670
SAM: He thinks I'm going to go into the water for
some fucking buttons.

03:08:04.670 --> 03:08:09.224
TRAVIS: I heard tell there was a button ship that
crashed right along the water.

03:08:09.224 --> 03:08:17.345
SAM: Oh, the old button ship legend, really?! Oh!
Buttonbeard the Pirate?!

03:08:17.345 --> 03:08:18.119
TRAVIS: Yep.

03:08:18.119 --> 03:08:20.786
SAM: He had buttons for beards!

03:08:20.786 --> 03:08:28.217
LIAM: Nott the Brave. We have things to accomplish
here. If you allow me, I could do what I have done

03:08:28.217 --> 03:08:35.672
in the past a little sneakily to help you cope
with this fear you have. If you allow me.

03:08:35.672 --> 03:08:42.415
SAM: I appreciate that, Caleb, but I've got my own
way of doing it.

03:08:42.415 --> 03:08:46.118
LIAM: Is it Mike Myers?

03:08:46.323 --> 03:08:50.588
TRAVIS: There might be bronzed shoes, maybe little
silver cups. Decoder rings.

03:08:50.588 --> 03:08:57.511
SAM: Ooh, those spoons? The little spoons, the
collectible ones? Fuck this guy.

03:08:58.601 --> 03:09:04.331
LIAM: We're not there yet, though, we're talking
in advance at this point? All in advance?

03:09:04.331 --> 03:09:05.173
LAURA: Yeah.

03:09:05.173 --> 03:09:07.033
TRAVIS: We're coming upon the area, right?

03:09:07.033 --> 03:09:16.190
MATT: Altogether with the eight of them, it cuts
the travel time down to five days. So you've got time.

03:09:16.190 --> 03:09:18.436
SAM: I'll think about it.

03:09:18.436 --> 03:09:22.555
TALIESIN: I'm going to be stocking us up on food
too, so that there's more than enough food and

03:09:22.555 --> 03:09:24.168
water for the whole group.

03:09:24.168 --> 03:09:33.060
SAM: Pewter? Plates? Those little collectible
plates from the Stanford Mint or whatever?

03:09:33.060 --> 03:09:37.432
LAURA: So we're going to hang around this area
before we get to the boat wrecks, yeah?

03:09:37.432 --> 03:09:39.117
TRAVIS: Yeah, I think so.

03:09:39.117 --> 03:09:40.107
LAURA: Okay.

03:09:40.107 --> 03:09:48.669
MATT: Okay, so taking your time, I would like you
to each to roll a base wisdom check for each pass

03:09:48.669 --> 03:09:51.698
as you go through.

03:09:51.698 --> 03:09:54.155
SAM: You two, right?

03:09:54.155 --> 03:09:58.081
MATT: Yes. d20 plus your wisdom modifier.

03:09:58.081 --> 03:09:59.713
TALIESIN: 19.

03:09:59.713 --> 03:10:00.813
LAURA: 12.

03:10:00.813 --> 03:10:02.912
MATT: Okay. Again.

03:10:05.341 --> 03:10:08.148
LAURA: God. Nine.

03:10:08.148 --> 03:10:12.226
TALIESIN: Oh, I'm doing save. I'm so sorry. Fuck,
I was doing the wrong--

03:10:12.226 --> 03:10:13.578
LAURA: Oh, shit! I was, too.

03:10:13.578 --> 03:10:15.272
MATT: This is just check. Add your wisdom
modifier.

03:10:15.272 --> 03:10:17.005
LAURA: Even lower.

03:10:17.005 --> 03:10:24.010
TALIESIN: I said 19? 16, and then 19.

03:10:24.010 --> 03:10:31.792
MATT: Okay. Roll again. Your third spell slot of
the first day, hitting this space and scanning the load.

03:10:32.399 --> 03:10:33.364
LAURA: 15.

03:10:33.364 --> 03:10:34.787
TALIESIN: 14.

03:10:35.200 --> 03:10:42.738
MATT: Okay, and you're utilizing your memory of
passage through here, as well as Orly's direction

03:10:42.738 --> 03:10:50.155
on this ocean. Go ahead and roll an intelligence
check for me.

03:10:54.848 --> 03:10:56.434
TRAVIS: 13.

03:10:56.434 --> 03:11:05.577
MATT: Okay. First day goes through. Nothing
catches your attention. You pass around, and then

03:11:05.577 --> 03:11:11.291
once you make it quite past the area, based on the
measurements, where you think that you recall it

03:11:11.291 --> 03:11:18.127
happening. The next day, you make a curved turn
and begin to head out to see some more land, as

03:11:18.127 --> 03:11:25.828
you can, to widen the perspective of your search.
For the second day, roll again.

03:11:27.387 --> 03:11:29.087
TALIESIN: Three?

03:11:29.087 --> 03:11:33.159
MATT: Three in a row, yeah. Unless you want to use
more spell slots to do more. So you can do your

03:11:33.159 --> 03:11:35.009
3rd-level to burn as well.

03:11:35.009 --> 03:11:37.820
LAURA: That's true. 20 on the first roll.

03:11:37.820 --> 03:11:40.307
TALIESIN: 20 on the first roll.

03:11:41.511 --> 03:11:43.165
LAURA: Lame on the second roll.

03:11:43.165 --> 03:11:44.930
TALIESIN: 14 on the second roll.

03:11:44.930 --> 03:11:49.212
MATT: (sneezes) Pardon me. Thank you. (sneezes)
Pardon. Thank you.

03:11:49.212 --> 03:11:50.849
SAM: You're a three-sneezer?

03:11:50.849 --> 03:11:52.952
MATT: I am, at least.

03:11:52.952 --> 03:11:54.682
LAURA: Should we try one more?

03:11:54.682 --> 03:11:58.482
TALIESIN: 16, 19. Yeah, let's blow another. What
else are we going to do for the day?

03:11:58.482 --> 03:11:59.258
MATT: Sure.

03:11:59.258 --> 03:12:02.373
LAURA: Motherfuck!

03:12:02.763 --> 03:12:04.118
TALIESIN: 24.

03:12:04.118 --> 03:12:05.369
LAURA: Six.

03:12:05.369 --> 03:12:07.958
MATT: Go ahead and roll an intelligence check for
you as well.

03:12:07.958 --> 03:12:09.570
MARISHA: Come on!

03:12:09.570 --> 03:12:11.425
LIAM: "Fuh-jord-y!"

03:12:11.948 --> 03:12:13.185
TRAVIS: 11.

03:12:13.185 --> 03:12:28.556
MATT: Okay. You go through the second day, and
towards the end, you, Caduceus, sense a brief

03:12:28.556 --> 03:12:35.874
moment where something ship-related catches your
attention, and then is gone.

03:12:35.874 --> 03:12:38.159
TALIESIN: I had a moment.

03:12:38.159 --> 03:12:39.150
TRAVIS: You did?

03:12:39.150 --> 03:12:42.771
TALIESIN: Yeah. It's gone now. Would I know
direction, even?

03:12:42.771 --> 03:12:44.904
MATT: Vague direction.

03:12:44.904 --> 03:12:46.075
TALIESIN: But we're moving, I know.

03:12:46.075 --> 03:12:48.808
MATT: Yeah, you're moving. So it's like, all
right, let's go ahead and turn it around.

03:12:48.808 --> 03:12:51.369
SAM: Just point. Caleb will know the direction.

03:12:51.369 --> 03:12:56.379
MATT: You turn the ship back in the direction of
where it goes. At the very end of the second day,

03:12:56.379 --> 03:13:04.665
just as dusk is starting to creep in, you make
your way back in the area, and you sense another hit.

03:13:04.665 --> 03:13:09.037
LAURA: Ooh. Should I use another 3rd-level spell
and try to find the orb-y thing?

03:13:09.037 --> 03:13:11.500
TALIESIN: Let's do one more.

03:13:11.500 --> 03:13:16.961
MATT: Okay. As you're attempting to find the orb,
roll a wisdom check.

03:13:16.961 --> 03:13:20.917
TALIESIN: I'll also join in for one more for that
as well. It's my last spell slot.

03:13:20.917 --> 03:13:23.599
MATT: Okay. You lose your concentration on the
Locate Object.

03:13:23.599 --> 03:13:28.697
TALIESIN: Oh. Okay, I'm still holding the boat.
That's fine.

03:13:28.697 --> 03:13:35.039
MATT: You circle around again. You've closed off a
distance, but you haven't quite located the

03:13:35.039 --> 03:13:40.035
specific area yet. You're trying to guide into a
vicinity. I mean, it's hard to really remember

03:13:40.035 --> 03:13:45.455
specifically where, when it's just open water and
a storm looming, especially. So you get to a

03:13:45.455 --> 03:13:48.911
certain point where you're like, I'm not sure I'm
being able to help, but you're starting to get

03:13:48.911 --> 03:13:54.181
something. You're not entirely sure. The
divination seems to be helping, or this aspect of

03:13:54.181 --> 03:14:02.762
your Locate spell. Evening comes to a close. You
ride the night out. The clouds are still thick.

03:14:02.762 --> 03:14:09.148
The next morning, you can attempt again if you
like, both of you.

03:14:09.148 --> 03:14:11.732
TRAVIS: Come on, you got it.

03:14:11.732 --> 03:14:14.071
SAM: Bless or something. Do a Bless!

03:14:14.071 --> 03:14:15.900
LAURA: I don't have Bless!

03:14:15.900 --> 03:14:17.007
SAM: No, <i>he</i> does.

03:14:17.007 --> 03:14:17.812
TALIESIN: I do.

03:14:17.812 --> 03:14:18.835
LAURA: Bless us!

03:14:18.835 --> 03:14:20.441
MATT: Make another intelligence check for me as
well.

03:14:20.441 --> 03:14:21.979
TALIESIN: Actually, this is a check, not a save,
so it wouldn't--

03:14:21.979 --> 03:14:28.604
LAURA: Oh, and I want to learn the cantrip
Guidance, but I don't know any good healers that

03:14:28.604 --> 03:14:30.880
can teach it to me.

03:14:30.880 --> 03:14:33.140
MARISHA: Druids can teach it, too.

03:14:33.837 --> 03:14:34.716
LAURA: 18.

03:14:34.716 --> 03:14:35.719
TALIESIN: 15.

03:14:35.719 --> 03:14:36.744
TRAVIS: 20.

03:14:36.744 --> 03:14:40.332
MATT: Okay. Roll again.

03:14:40.332 --> 03:14:42.879
SAM: One last one.

03:14:42.879 --> 03:14:44.500
MATT: This is your second spell slot used
today?

03:14:44.500 --> 03:14:45.529
TALIESIN: 19.

03:14:45.529 --> 03:14:47.356
LAURA: Motherfuck. I'm going to use a third.

03:14:47.356 --> 03:14:48.655
TALIESIN: That was my third, was 19.

03:14:48.655 --> 03:14:52.391
MATT: Okay.

03:14:52.391 --> 03:14:54.503
LAURA: 21.

03:14:54.503 --> 03:14:59.238
MATT: Okay. Between the 21 and your 20 intellect
in guiding the ship around, you find yourself now

03:14:59.238 --> 03:15:03.829
collecting a secondary blip. Once again, on the
ship, not on the eye.

03:15:03.829 --> 03:15:05.124
LAURA: I was on the orb.

03:15:05.124 --> 03:15:06.793
MATT: You're concentrating on the orb, or the
ship?

03:15:06.793 --> 03:15:08.171
LAURA: I was concentrating on the ball.

03:15:08.171 --> 03:15:10.924
MATT: The ball? You find nothing.

03:15:10.924 --> 03:15:19.319
TRAVIS: I think that means it's probably not down
there, but I'd still like to take a look.

03:15:19.319 --> 03:15:21.464
LIAM: Are we close? What are you telling us?

03:15:21.464 --> 03:15:25.919
TRAVIS: I think so. We're starting to round an
area that I think we could probably fan out and

03:15:25.919 --> 03:15:29.299
explore amongst the seven of us.

03:15:29.509 --> 03:15:41.519
LIAM: I just got my cat back, but if you want an
octopus to look on the bottom, you have it.

03:15:41.519 --> 03:15:42.960
TALIESIN: That's a very good idea.

03:15:42.960 --> 03:15:47.198
TRAVIS: That is, actually. If it wouldn't be too
much trouble, Caleb, that would be--

03:15:47.198 --> 03:15:55.615
LIAM: Yeah, I have just enough incense to-- yeah
sure, let's make an octopus. Cat-shaped. An

03:15:55.615 --> 03:15:57.484
octopus-shaped cat.

03:15:57.484 --> 03:16:00.816
MARISHA: Oh wow. How far does your octopus'
connection go for?

03:16:00.816 --> 03:16:05.390
LIAM: Well, I can tell him to go look and he'll
come back to me. I can see through him for--

03:16:05.390 --> 03:16:07.756
MARISHA: Yeah, but how far is your connection?

03:16:07.756 --> 03:16:16.595
LIAM: It's a thousand feet. To <i>watch</i>, but he can
go and come back, and I trust him. He's Frumpkin.

03:16:16.595 --> 03:16:24.776
I pull out my book and I set it on the deck and I
start working on turning <i>my cat</i> into an octopus.

03:16:24.776 --> 03:16:27.262
SAM: Does this mean we don't have to go in the
water?

03:16:27.262 --> 03:16:29.654
TALIESIN: Oh, this means we'll probably have to go
in the water.

03:16:29.654 --> 03:16:32.426
SAM: What? Why? He's got an octopus.

03:16:32.426 --> 03:16:36.275
LIAM: An hour later, an octopus pops out, if we
wait that long.

03:16:36.275 --> 03:16:38.348
TRAVIS: Yeah, I'd be okay with it.

03:16:38.348 --> 03:16:39.979
MATT: So you create a Frumpkin octopus.

03:16:39.979 --> 03:16:47.090
LIAM: Yeah. (sighs) Well, we had one or two days
together. Just throw him off.

03:16:47.090 --> 03:16:53.118
MATT: (splashing) Frumpkin makes his way in the
darkness.

03:16:53.118 --> 03:16:56.839
TALIESIN: I'm also going to put Bless on the
octopus before it.

03:16:56.839 --> 03:16:58.782
MATT: Okay. How long does it last?

03:16:58.782 --> 03:17:03.711
TALIESIN: It's one minute.

03:17:03.711 --> 03:17:10.864
LIAM: So I'll watch for the first thousand feet,
but I assume he goes beyond that, because it's the

03:17:10.864 --> 03:17:18.525
ocean, so he keeps going down and down and down. I
will tell him to look for this wreck, for what we

03:17:18.525 --> 03:17:21.874
are looking for, and when he finds it to come back
and tell me about it.

03:17:21.874 --> 03:17:24.324
MATT: Okay. Make a perception check for Frumpkin.

03:17:28.024 --> 03:17:29.244
LIAM: 13.

03:17:29.244 --> 03:17:37.927
MATT: Okay. About an hour goes by. Nothing. Roll
again.

03:17:41.165 --> 03:17:42.687
LIAM: 17.

03:17:42.687 --> 03:17:51.523
MATT: Frumpkin goes beyond your visual range for a
bit. You start getting worried, and then Frumpkin

03:17:51.523 --> 03:17:57.171
returns and is making his way quickly towards the
ship.

03:17:57.171 --> 03:17:59.606
LIAM: If he's within 1000, we have a connection.

03:17:59.606 --> 03:18:00.883
MATT: 100-foot is the connection.

03:18:00.883 --> 03:18:01.984
LIAM: A hundred? Thank you.

03:18:01.984 --> 03:18:04.943
MARISHA: Maybe he'll see Dashilla.

03:18:04.943 --> 03:18:06.309
LIAM: Maybe it's 10,000.

03:18:06.309 --> 03:18:11.459
MATT: Technically, the distance doesn't matter for
what you can see through his eyes. It's a 100 feet

03:18:11.459 --> 03:18:12.596
for it to communicate.

03:18:12.596 --> 03:18:16.486
LIAM: Right, we've established that. I can see
indefinitely. That's what we established early in

03:18:16.486 --> 03:18:20.158
the campaign with the circus, but I can't
communicate with him.

03:18:20.158 --> 03:18:25.249
MATT: Correct, during that time. So yeah, you
watch through Frumpkin's eyes as he makes his way

03:18:25.249 --> 03:18:36.147
toward the-- finally finding the floor of this
ocean. Over this second hour of his search, he

03:18:36.147 --> 03:18:42.991
catches one shape that is emerging like an obelisk
on the bottom of the ocean. Upon getting close

03:18:42.991 --> 03:18:53.356
enough, you can see it looks to be the front of a
wrecked ship, itself damaged and caked in

03:18:53.356 --> 03:19:02.944
minerals, ocean floor plant life, barnacles. It
appears to be a damaged ship.

03:19:06.214 --> 03:19:08.370
SAM: Does it have a name?

03:19:08.433 --> 03:19:10.275
LIAM: I don't hear any of you.

03:19:10.275 --> 03:19:12.238
SAM: (shouting) Does it have a name?

03:19:12.238 --> 03:19:14.763
MARISHA: You're in my ear. Ow!

03:19:14.763 --> 03:19:16.906
SAM: Sorry.

03:19:16.906 --> 03:19:22.291
LIAM: Ooh, he has found the ship. This is a
reminder I can't hear any of you. I don't want to

03:19:22.291 --> 03:19:26.497
disconnect. Don't give me wet willies.

03:19:26.497 --> 03:19:28.428
LAURA: I give him a wet willie.

03:19:28.428 --> 03:19:31.818
SAM: Six wet willies.

03:19:31.818 --> 03:19:34.549
TRAVIS: His ears are just dripping saliva.

03:19:34.549 --> 03:19:37.636
MATT and LAURA: (groaning)

03:19:37.636 --> 03:19:44.043
MATT: Okay. Frumpkin does a circle on it, before
feeling confident that he's discovered at least

03:19:44.043 --> 03:19:50.775
something of interest, and then beelines it back
to the Squalleater.

03:19:50.775 --> 03:19:57.792
LIAM: Who's a good boy?! You are the best cat that
was ever put on this planet!

03:19:57.792 --> 03:20:00.893
MATT: Then Frumpkin is now there at the surface of
the water, without really a way getting back into

03:20:00.893 --> 03:20:02.041
the ship.

03:20:02.041 --> 03:20:03.788
LIAM: Oh yeah?

03:20:03.788 --> 03:20:05.561
MATT: Yeah, there you go, back in your shoulder.

03:20:05.561 --> 03:20:12.337
LIAM: Oh, come here you. You are the most
important member of this team and don't let

03:20:12.337 --> 03:20:16.747
Beauregard tell you different. Or Nott.

03:20:16.747 --> 03:20:20.911
MARISHA: Do you ever feel like your relationship
with your cat is hindering building stronger

03:20:20.911 --> 03:20:23.202
relationships with human people?

03:20:23.202 --> 03:20:24.915
SAM: I've told him that a lot of times.

03:20:24.915 --> 03:20:28.795
MARISHA: I feel concerned about you sometimes.

03:20:28.937 --> 03:20:32.021
LIAM: Yeah, that is so silly, isn't it? Silly, yes
it is.

03:20:32.021 --> 03:20:34.627
SAM: Tell us what he found!

03:20:34.627 --> 03:20:41.306
LIAM: He found the boat, Nott. he found the boat. He will
lead us to the boat. He found it. He did it.

03:20:41.306 --> 03:20:42.687
SAM: That's great.

03:20:42.687 --> 03:20:50.194
TRAVIS: That is great news. Does anybody not
want to join? Really? You want to stay up here?

03:20:50.194 --> 03:20:53.043
SAM: How far down is it?

03:20:53.043 --> 03:20:54.814
LIAM: It's the bottom of the ocean.

03:20:54.814 --> 03:20:56.226
SAM: And how far is that?

03:20:56.226 --> 03:20:58.165
LIAM: It's thousands of feet.

03:20:58.165 --> 03:20:59.651
LAURA: No, it wasn't a thousand.

03:20:59.651 --> 03:21:01.213
LIAM: Thousands of feet.

03:21:01.213 --> 03:21:03.340
MATT: Over an hour.

03:21:03.340 --> 03:21:06.523
SAM: Ugh, fuck that. No way!

03:21:06.523 --> 03:21:12.119
MATT: Like, just barely. From the distance where
you are now. It'd be just under a thousand if you

03:21:12.119 --> 03:21:17.603
were right over, but you're not entirely certain
how far. The boat isn't set for that currently.

03:21:17.603 --> 03:21:19.534
LIAM: You have a method to bring us down there.

03:21:19.534 --> 03:21:20.461
SAM: What is this method?

03:21:20.461 --> 03:21:23.143
LIAM: Describe it to me. I've read a bit. Explain
it to the goblin.

03:21:23.143 --> 03:21:30.134
TRAVIS: I'll cast a little-- on you and for 24
hours, you can breathe underwater freely.

03:21:30.134 --> 03:21:31.546
LIAM: That is a whole day.

03:21:31.546 --> 03:21:33.884
SAM: But you still have to move through the water,
you still have to swim through it--

03:21:33.884 --> 03:21:37.212
TRAVIS: Yeah. You could hold onto my shoulders if
you wanted to.

03:21:37.212 --> 03:21:40.091
MARISHA: Could we give ourselves some weights to
get us down there?

03:21:40.091 --> 03:21:42.253
MATT: You've got weight.

03:21:42.253 --> 03:21:44.705
MARISHA: Concrete shoes!

03:21:44.705 --> 03:21:47.382
SAM: Sounds terrifying.

03:21:47.382 --> 03:21:49.852
TRAVIS: Actually, we could take a few of the
cannonballs to just--

03:21:49.852 --> 03:21:51.602
MARISHA: We should have weights that weigh us down
there.

03:21:51.602 --> 03:21:56.755
LAURA: Will the breathing underwater, will that
make it to where our ears won't hurt really bad?

03:21:56.755 --> 03:22:00.068
Because I hear when you go down underwater, your
ears hurt really bad.

03:22:00.068 --> 03:22:02.265
TRAVIS: That's because of the air. You're going to
have to equalize.

03:22:02.265 --> 03:22:04.003
SAM: Your ears hurt bad too? Jesus.

03:22:04.003 --> 03:22:07.087
TRAVIS: But if you're breathing water, there's no
air to expand or contract.

03:22:07.087 --> 03:22:11.286
MARISHA: Won't you crush under the pressure of the
water after a certain point?.

03:22:11.286 --> 03:22:15.242
TRAVIS: After a certain depth. There's only one
way to find out.

03:22:15.242 --> 03:22:21.280
LIAM: Now, you people have not read about-- you
don't understand magic. It's not like that. I want

03:22:21.280 --> 03:22:22.941
to try this.

03:22:22.941 --> 03:22:28.809
TRAVIS: I know. I do, too. Those that want to
join, join me at the rail. I'll jump on and sit on the rail.

03:22:28.809 --> 03:22:32.018
LAURA: No, wait! We have to get a good night's
sleep. We just used all of our spells finding this shit!

03:22:32.018 --> 03:22:35.494
MARISHA: Oh yeah. That's a good point.

03:22:35.494 --> 03:22:40.169
TALIESIN: Let's have them. Let's tell the crew
what's up. Early in the morning, at first light.

03:22:40.169 --> 03:22:43.316
LIAM: It's too late. Fjord's in the water,
swimming around.

03:22:43.316 --> 03:22:44.590
MARISHA: Caduceus, you making breakfast?

03:22:44.590 --> 03:22:48.292
TALIESIN: I'm always making breakfast. I'm not
going to even use the weird plants.

03:22:48.292 --> 03:22:50.412
MARISHA: I'll get up for Caduceus' breakfast.

03:22:50.412 --> 03:22:54.156
TALIESIN: I've been putting that weird fruit in
everyone's food for a week now, by the way. Just

03:22:54.156 --> 03:22:55.658
so we're clear.

03:22:55.658 --> 03:22:56.974
LIAM: In minimal amounts, or full dose?

03:22:56.974 --> 03:22:58.260
MATT: The stuff that you found at Urukayxl?

03:22:58.260 --> 03:22:59.681
TALIESIN: Just kidding, but wouldn't that be
great?

03:22:59.681 --> 03:23:00.757
MATT: That would be amazing

03:23:00.757 --> 03:23:02.582
TALIESIN: Everyone's just be like, "Wow!"

03:23:02.582 --> 03:23:07.843
LIAM: There was no battle. There was no battle
with Avantika, man!

03:23:07.843 --> 03:23:10.173
TRAVIS: We're not on the boat, we're in sand.

03:23:10.173 --> 03:23:11.569
LAURA: There's no nothing.

03:23:11.569 --> 03:23:15.701
LIAM: We're sitting in your mom's sitting room
right now.

03:23:15.701 --> 03:23:20.372
MATT: You look up and on the side, there's the
Plank King and Avantika looking at him. He's like,

03:23:20.372 --> 03:23:22.029
"Where you'd find these people?"

03:23:22.029 --> 03:23:26.251
(laughter)

03:23:26.251 --> 03:23:33.385
MATT: All right, so you guys have another night's
rest. As you wake up the next morning, it is

03:23:33.385 --> 03:23:39.430
raining. There appears to be a small storm making
its way in there.

03:23:39.430 --> 03:23:43.847
MARISHA: Are the fish out? Fish always come out
when it rains.

03:23:43.847 --> 03:23:53.528
MATT: Well, once you make it in the ocean, you'll
find out. Noticeably, Yasha is energized with the

03:23:53.528 --> 03:24:01.375
coming of the storm. Seems to be in more energetic
spirits than you're used to seeing her. You guys

03:24:01.375 --> 03:24:05.755
complete your meal for breakfast. You gather your
supplies. What are you going to do?

03:24:05.755 --> 03:24:11.426
TRAVIS: I'll leave Orly in command while we head
under. To complete this spell, I'm going to need

03:24:11.426 --> 03:24:14.345
everyone to hold hands in a circle.

03:24:14.345 --> 03:24:22.445
MARISHA: I would like to sing a little Kumbaya
song and refresh everybody on the Diver's Grave,

03:24:22.445 --> 03:24:25.014
which is where we are.

03:24:25.014 --> 03:24:26.501
SAM: Are you going to sing that Diver's Grave
song?

03:24:26.501 --> 03:24:29.618
MARISHA: (singing) Kumbaya, the cursed woman--

03:24:29.618 --> 03:24:31.691
LAURA: (singing) Dashilla the Dreadful--

03:24:31.691 --> 03:24:36.830
MARISHA: (singing) Kumbaya Dashilla, Dashilla with
claws that grasp.

03:24:36.830 --> 03:24:38.904
TRAVIS: Do we need to have the rights to that
song?

03:24:38.904 --> 03:24:40.951
MARISHA: (singing) Oh god I hope not.

03:24:40.951 --> 03:24:42.430
LAURA: (singing) And a hungry eye.

03:24:42.430 --> 03:24:47.659
MARISHA: (singing) She's got a hungry eye and with
a lantern light. Dashilla, the cursed woman,

03:24:47.659 --> 03:24:50.021
treasures in her eyes.

03:24:50.021 --> 03:24:51.438
SAM: This is nice.

03:24:51.438 --> 03:24:52.713
TRAVIS: Uh-huh. Cool.

03:24:52.713 --> 03:24:54.513
MARISHA: (singing) Dashilla the cursed.

03:24:54.513 --> 03:24:56.457
LIAM: I am casting Mage Armor during whatever the
fuck this is.

03:24:56.457 --> 03:24:57.089
MATT: Okay.

03:24:57.089 --> 03:24:58.215
SAM: That was good.

03:24:58.215 --> 03:24:59.335
MARISHA: I'm just saying.

03:24:59.335 --> 03:25:03.279
LAURA: Did you give us anything for that? Did we
get bonuses or did we just get to hear you sing?

03:25:03.279 --> 03:25:06.244
MARISHA: No, that was Keyleth. Sorry.

03:25:06.244 --> 03:25:08.885
LAURA: It was literally just Beau singing.

03:25:08.885 --> 03:25:10.842
MARISHA: Just me trying to do--

03:25:10.842 --> 03:25:13.718
TRAVIS: Well, while it's happening, because it was
such a good song, I will cast Underwater Breathing

03:25:13.718 --> 03:25:16.362
on all seven of us.

03:25:16.362 --> 03:25:20.078
MARISHA: My song was that good.

03:25:20.078 --> 03:25:24.724
MATT: All right, all of you now have the
capability for the next 24 hours to breathe

03:25:24.724 --> 03:25:31.292
underwater. Your lungs feel heavier than they do
while you breathe air. It's unique. No gills

03:25:31.292 --> 03:25:37.399
sprout from the side of your neck, per se, but the
air itself seems to have a weight to it, and

03:25:37.399 --> 03:25:43.051
you're like (exhales). It's still breathable air,
but the process seems to have changed a bit.

03:25:43.051 --> 03:25:44.400
LIAM: It's the abyss.

03:25:44.400 --> 03:25:51.739
MARISHA: In preparation for this, I went and I
gathered a few sandbags. Took some burlap, filled

03:25:51.739 --> 03:25:53.796
them with--

03:25:53.796 --> 03:25:55.970
MATT: There's no sand to fill them with out in the
ocean, unfortunately.

03:25:55.970 --> 03:25:57.273
MARISHA: Uh-huh.

03:25:57.273 --> 03:25:58.511
TRAVIS: Cannonballs?

03:25:58.511 --> 03:26:01.323
MARISHA: Okay, yeah sure. I got the
eight-pounders.

03:26:01.323 --> 03:26:02.813
SAM: You have to clear that with me.

03:26:02.813 --> 03:26:06.323
MARISHA: I brought out a few-- but look, I'm the
barrel person.

03:26:06.323 --> 03:26:12.415
MATT: As a note, too, when the Squalleater came to
port that night, Darktow was resupplied with

03:26:12.415 --> 03:26:16.650
cannonballs on board. For those who are keeping
track, which would be--

03:26:16.650 --> 03:26:17.686
SAM: Me!

03:26:17.686 --> 03:26:24.233
MATT: You. The ship currently has a cache of 30
cannonballs.

03:26:24.233 --> 03:26:27.829
SAM: Nice. How many are you taking?

03:26:27.829 --> 03:26:32.229
TRAVIS: Well, we could just use four and have two
people hold on to the same cannonball.

03:26:32.229 --> 03:26:37.360
LIAM: Yeah, that makes sense. Nott and I are
sharing one.

03:26:37.360 --> 03:26:42.472
MATT: Okay. You maneuver the boat slowly also
closer to where Frumpkin saw because when Frumpkin

03:26:42.472 --> 03:26:46.410
found it, it was at an angle away from you, which
is how it was just beyond the range of a thousand

03:26:46.410 --> 03:26:52.012
feet. Moving over, it's probably close to 700 feet
below.

03:26:52.012 --> 03:26:56.005
LIAM: So Frumpkin is pinwheeling in front of all
of us leading the way.

03:26:56.005 --> 03:26:57.210
MATT: Okay.

03:26:57.210 --> 03:26:59.759
TRAVIS: I don't suppose we have 700 feet of rope
on this ship, do we?

03:26:59.759 --> 03:27:03.130
LAURA: Probably not.

03:27:03.130 --> 03:27:07.288
SAM: We have an anchor. It can only go down so
far, but I don't know how--

03:27:07.288 --> 03:27:08.939
MARISHA: That's true. How far does the anchor go?

03:27:08.939 --> 03:27:10.778
SAM: 200 feet? 100 feet?

03:27:10.778 --> 03:27:12.126
MATT: It's not going to go that far.

03:27:12.126 --> 03:27:16.163
LIAM: No, ships don't go to anchor in the middle
of the ocean. They just float.

03:27:16.163 --> 03:27:21.516
TRAVIS: If you're ready, take a seat on the rail
and I'll hop up and put my butt out towards the sea.

03:27:21.516 --> 03:27:23.074
LAURA: It's going to be dark down there.

03:27:23.074 --> 03:27:24.543
MARISHA: Do we have light spells?

03:27:24.543 --> 03:27:26.228
LAURA: I don't.

03:27:26.228 --> 03:27:27.460
TRAVIS: Yasha does.

03:27:27.460 --> 03:27:28.534
TALIESIN: I do.

03:27:28.534 --> 03:27:30.066
LIAM: (popping)

03:27:30.066 --> 03:27:31.817
MATT: Dancing Lights. You cast Light on?

03:27:31.817 --> 03:27:32.895
TALIESIN: On my staff.

03:27:32.895 --> 03:27:35.136
MATT: Yasha casts Light on her sword, the
Magician's Judge.

03:27:35.136 --> 03:27:36.434
SAM: I need a minute!

03:27:36.434 --> 03:27:37.482
TRAVIS: You need a minute?

03:27:37.482 --> 03:27:39.395
SAM: I'm going to drink heavily.

03:27:39.395 --> 03:27:41.506
MATT: To the point where you're intoxicated?

03:27:41.506 --> 03:27:43.090
SAM: To the point of intoxication.

03:27:43.090 --> 03:27:43.983
MATT: Okay.

03:27:43.983 --> 03:27:52.217
LIAM: That's important because I switched the
Transmuter's Stone away from darkvision, so I

03:27:52.217 --> 03:27:56.884
cannot see in low light, so it's got to be guiding
lights for me.

03:27:56.884 --> 03:28:01.348
LAURA: I'm going to take Sprinkle out of my
hood--

03:28:01.348 --> 03:28:02.711
TRAVIS: Ah, smart.

03:28:02.711 --> 03:28:05.280
MARISHA: Oh, buddy.

03:28:05.280 --> 03:28:11.317
MATT: This poor little-- it's better over the days
that it's been able to spend with you since

03:28:11.317 --> 03:28:15.605
Darktow, but this ferret's been through quite a
few experiences.

03:28:15.605 --> 03:28:23.127
LAURA: You're like a super ferret. You're like the
strongest little animal I've ever seen. I mean, really.

03:28:23.127 --> 03:28:26.144
MATT: (ferret chattering) Then he curls up. He
hears a loud noise (startled chittering).

03:28:26.144 --> 03:28:27.365
TALIESIN: Scarred for life.

03:28:27.365 --> 03:28:28.900
TRAVIS: He's just fucked.

03:28:28.900 --> 03:28:30.189
LAURA: Orly?

03:28:30.189 --> 03:28:31.553
MARISHA: He's a rescue.

03:28:31.553 --> 03:28:36.370
MATT: "Hmm?" I can't remember which eye it is
anymore. I'll have to go check. "Mmm?"

03:28:36.370 --> 03:28:41.912
LAURA: Do you like weasels?

03:28:41.912 --> 03:28:44.757
SAM: That's a weird opener.

03:28:44.757 --> 03:28:47.526
TALIESIN: It never ends well. There's no right
answer to that question.

03:28:47.526 --> 03:28:48.741
MATT: "Why?"

03:28:48.741 --> 03:28:52.481
LAURA: I have a weasel and I don't want to take
him underwater.

03:28:52.481 --> 03:28:54.433
TALIESIN: Water weasel.

03:28:54.433 --> 03:28:59.344
MATT: You watch as Orly's head retracts into the
shell slightly with this look of--

03:28:59.344 --> 03:29:01.047
LAURA: Orly.

03:29:01.047 --> 03:29:07.100
MATT: Marius steps up and goes like, "I'm happy to
look after him. Actually been quite a while since

03:29:07.100 --> 03:29:09.004
"I've seen a pet."

03:29:09.004 --> 03:29:10.350
MARISHA: Wait. Who said that?

03:29:10.350 --> 03:29:12.001
SAM and MATT: Marius LePual.

03:29:12.001 --> 03:29:15.289
MATT: Who you've dragged all the way from
Nicodranas--

03:29:15.289 --> 03:29:19.148
TRAVIS: But he's got a good tan now and some
scars, his clothes are kind of fucked up.

03:29:19.148 --> 03:29:21.923
LAURA: He's like Guy Threepwood now.

03:29:21.923 --> 03:29:26.269
MATT: He does look a little more ocean-wearied. As
prim and proper and put together as Marius was at

03:29:26.269 --> 03:29:30.272
Nicodranas, he's definitely rocking more of a
Pirates of Penzance thing now.

03:29:30.272 --> 03:29:34.393
LIAM: He went from level two to three. Doing
good.

03:29:34.393 --> 03:29:36.643
LAURA: You'll take good care of him?

03:29:36.643 --> 03:29:37.772
MATT: "Of course!"

03:29:37.772 --> 03:29:44.267
LAURA: If you don't, I will know and I will give
you a tattoo. If you do take good care of him,

03:29:44.267 --> 03:29:48.668
though, I will give you a better tattoo.

03:29:48.668 --> 03:29:51.362
MATT: "Are those the only options?"

03:29:51.362 --> 03:29:53.375
LAURA: I mean, if you want.

03:29:53.375 --> 03:29:56.632
MATT: "Okay. Hello-- oh!" (nervous laughter)

03:29:56.632 --> 03:30:03.020
LAURA: He likes to eat fruit. He likes to eat
cheese. He likes to eat bugs.

03:30:03.020 --> 03:30:04.311
MATT: "Right."

03:30:04.311 --> 03:30:07.429
SAM: I think we only have the one food that you've
been creating on the ship.

03:30:07.429 --> 03:30:09.143
LAURA: He likes it if you talk to him.

03:30:09.143 --> 03:30:10.125
TALIESIN: We have bugs and cheese.

03:30:10.125 --> 03:30:11.043
LAURA: Yeah, we got bugs and cheese.

03:30:11.043 --> 03:30:17.149
MATT: "Okay. Well, come. Let's get you some cheese
and-- oh, that's my hand you're peeing in, okay."

03:30:17.149 --> 03:30:18.771
TALIESIN: We always got bugs and cheese, man.

03:30:18.771 --> 03:30:22.181
MATT: He carries him off. All right, you gather
your supplies, you gather your cannonballs.

03:30:22.181 --> 03:30:24.313
MARISHA: Oh my god.

03:30:24.313 --> 03:30:28.561
TRAVIS: On the count of three, when you're ready,
you'll lean backwards off the rail and fall into

03:30:28.561 --> 03:30:29.662
the water.

03:30:29.662 --> 03:30:31.513
LAURA: On the count of three, when you're ready.

03:30:31.513 --> 03:30:41.505
MATT: As it stands, the cannonballs are smooth,
solid metal. How are you bringing them down with you?

03:30:41.505 --> 03:30:42.761
TALIESIN: There's a couple of options here.

03:30:42.761 --> 03:30:44.123
LAURA: We're going to hold on to the sides.

03:30:44.123 --> 03:30:48.097
TALIESIN: Well, we want to be able to carry them
so if we have some small bags maybe?

03:30:48.097 --> 03:30:50.421
MARISHA: Like rope or chain? Oh! Yeah.

03:30:50.421 --> 03:30:52.228
TALIESIN: We can just put them in a bag that we
can hold.

03:30:52.228 --> 03:30:55.231
MATT: That can be done. You do have a few sacks.

03:30:55.231 --> 03:31:02.151
LIAM: They're iron, right? I would say that with
Nott piggybacking, Caleb would take his dagger and

03:31:02.151 --> 03:31:06.731
transmute it into iron to meld with the cannonball
and grip it that way.

03:31:06.731 --> 03:31:08.671
TRAVIS: Ooh, make a little handle.

03:31:08.671 --> 03:31:10.372
MATT: I'll allow it, yeah.

03:31:10.372 --> 03:31:12.023
LIAM: Thanks.

03:31:12.647 --> 03:31:16.202
MATT: As you place the dagger against it, there's
a brief moment where the dagger seems to shift

03:31:16.202 --> 03:31:20.405
energy and you slip it inside of it and at that
point, the handle is now solid with the

03:31:20.405 --> 03:31:24.973
cannonball, so one cannonball has a handle.
Another one, a sack around it. Actually, a few of

03:31:24.973 --> 03:31:26.818
them you can put sacks around it, so--

03:31:26.818 --> 03:31:28.772
TRAVIS: You want to share a cannonball, Jester?

03:31:28.772 --> 03:31:29.671
LAURA: Sure, Fjord.

03:31:29.671 --> 03:31:30.370
TRAVIS: Okay.

03:31:30.370 --> 03:31:36.692
MARISHA: Cad, you and me? What's Yasha doing, is
she coming with us or is she invigorated by the storm?

03:31:36.692 --> 03:31:38.289
TRAVIS: She gets her own cannonball because
she's--

03:31:38.289 --> 03:31:39.355
MATT: Yeah, she's coming with you.

03:31:39.355 --> 03:31:44.408
TRAVIS: Yeah, she's just like that. Just holding
it like a beast.

03:31:44.408 --> 03:31:45.590
LIAM: Palming it.

03:31:45.590 --> 03:31:48.073
MARISHA: Yeah. Globetrotters.

03:31:48.073 --> 03:31:52.173
TRAVIS: Ready? One, two, three.

03:31:52.173 --> 03:31:53.120
LAURA: Oh god!

03:31:53.120 --> 03:31:54.351
SAM: (screaming)

03:31:54.351 --> 03:32:06.532
MATT: You splash and break the surface of the
ocean. As you all begin to sink slowly beneath the

03:32:06.532 --> 03:32:12.297
waves, the light begins to get darker and darker
the further down you pass. The shades of

03:32:12.297 --> 03:32:20.677
green-blue begin to turn to a deep green-brown,
and even that light begins to fade, just having

03:32:20.677 --> 03:32:26.331
the few points of light that you are bringing
along with yourselves towards the bottom of the ocean.

03:32:26.331 --> 03:32:29.523
TRAVIS: I try to catch Nott. How is she doing?

03:32:29.523 --> 03:32:31.392
SAM: Eyes totally closed.

03:32:31.392 --> 03:32:33.414
TRAVIS: Are you breathing well? I give her a--

03:32:33.414 --> 03:32:35.253
MATT: Nott has not taken a breath yet, actually.

03:32:35.253 --> 03:32:37.202
TRAVIS: International sign for breathe.

03:32:37.202 --> 03:32:43.371
MATT: You get to a point, Nott, where your lungs
hurt so much you cannot help but breathe in, and

03:32:43.371 --> 03:32:47.090
there is a moment of panic as suddenly water
rushes into your lungs and the nightmare you've

03:32:47.090 --> 03:32:49.287
had many times kicks in.

03:32:49.287 --> 03:32:54.057
TRAVIS: Actually, that means go down.

03:32:54.057 --> 03:32:57.252
SAM: Shit.

03:33:03.847 --> 03:33:07.369
MATT: It takes a little bit to adjust and anxiety
is still spiked in you, but you begin to find

03:33:07.369 --> 03:33:12.715
yourself breathing water in and out-- like thicker
air, but still air-- and it's more comfortable

03:33:12.715 --> 03:33:14.887
than you expected.

03:33:14.887 --> 03:33:16.565
LAURA: Can we talk down here?

03:33:16.565 --> 03:33:17.611
MATT: You can.

03:33:17.611 --> 03:33:18.521
LAURA: We can?

03:33:18.521 --> 03:33:23.756
MATT: It doesn't have the same volume you do above
water, which means you can cast spells underwater

03:33:23.756 --> 03:33:24.609
without issue.

03:33:24.609 --> 03:33:25.185
LIAM: We can?

03:33:25.185 --> 03:33:33.141
MATT: Yes, same as you had before. It carries
vibration and sound travels far, but it loses

03:33:33.141 --> 03:33:39.293
enunciation at longer distances, but you can hear
voices longer.

03:33:39.293 --> 03:33:43.685
LIAM: There are four globules of light slowly
circling around.

03:33:43.685 --> 03:33:50.474
SAM: (gurgling) When we get back to the surface, I
will kill you.

03:33:50.474 --> 03:33:52.067
MARISHA: That was pretty good, though.

03:33:52.067 --> 03:33:54.569
MATT: Oh, this is going to be awful.

03:33:54.569 --> 03:33:59.388
TRAVIS: (gurgling) Well listen, Nott, as long as
we're down here--

03:33:59.388 --> 03:34:03.476
LIAM: Cannot do that joke anymore. That joke has
past.

03:34:05.613 --> 03:34:14.277
MATT: Your feet find the bottom of the ocean after
minutes. Ten minutes. Who knows how much time has

03:34:14.277 --> 03:34:18.294
past? It seemed longer than you expected until you
eventually you hit the bottom of the ocean.

03:34:18.294 --> 03:34:20.041
MARISHA: Look up. What do I see?

03:34:20.041 --> 03:34:25.829
MATT: You see the faint bit of light above where
it marks where the sunlight is hitting the waves,

03:34:25.829 --> 03:34:34.720
but it's an impossible distance from you from this
perspective. There are heavy, slowly shifting

03:34:34.720 --> 03:34:46.062
arms, waving tassels of kelp and sea vegetation
slightly drifting and moving with every faint bit

03:34:46.062 --> 03:34:52.512
of water that gets maneuvered through with each
wave and push as it goes, and you can feel it move

03:34:52.512 --> 03:34:58.006
you a few inches and you have to readjust as each
one pushes through.

03:34:59.876 --> 03:35:02.607
LAURA: It's like another world.

03:35:03.832 --> 03:35:07.719
MATT: You realize there shouldn't be waves this
deep necessarily.

03:35:07.719 --> 03:35:09.335
MARISHA: Where are they coming from?

03:35:09.335 --> 03:35:17.021
MATT: You glance over and watch as a large
creature is not that far away from you.

03:35:17.021 --> 03:35:19.288
LAURA: I cast Pass Without a Trace on all of us.

03:35:19.288 --> 03:35:21.574
TALIESIN: I dim the light.

03:35:21.574 --> 03:35:24.777
LIAM: Can't see anymore.

03:35:24.777 --> 03:35:33.992
MATT: You hear a faint (whale singing) and glance
over the left. You can see a whale making its way

03:35:33.992 --> 03:35:37.812
through the water about 50, 60 feet from you.

03:35:37.812 --> 03:35:39.108
LIAM: I can't see shit.

03:35:39.108 --> 03:35:40.672
MATT: Not with a--

03:35:40.672 --> 03:35:42.719
MARISHA: I put my goggles on by the way--

03:35:42.719 --> 03:35:44.604
LIAM: You're good. I'm blind and are you blind?

03:35:44.604 --> 03:35:52.231
MATT: He still has the light. You can still see;
Caduceus and Yasha still have the light on their weapons.

03:35:52.231 --> 03:35:58.793
TALIESIN: My weapon glows but I did snuff it down.
I was waiting until we knew that we were okay. I

03:35:58.793 --> 03:36:00.746
move my light over to him.

03:36:00.746 --> 03:36:04.378
MATT: The whale continues on, slowly moving, not
really acknowledging your presence. You can see

03:36:04.378 --> 03:36:06.828
two other smaller whales alongside it.

03:36:06.828 --> 03:36:08.731
TRAVIS: Aww, baby calves.

03:36:08.731 --> 03:36:16.302
TALIESIN: Hey. Technically they can understand
me.

03:36:16.302 --> 03:36:23.480
MATT: Everyone make an investigation check. This
will be perception. Underwater, perception.

03:36:23.480 --> 03:36:24.999
SAM: Disadvantage!

03:36:24.999 --> 03:36:26.475
MATT: Yep.

03:36:26.475 --> 03:36:27.988
MARISHA: Natural one.

03:36:27.988 --> 03:36:29.698
TRAVIS: 19.

03:36:29.698 --> 03:36:30.776
LIAM: Nine.

03:36:30.776 --> 03:36:32.427
SAM: Four.

03:36:32.427 --> 03:36:33.533
LAURA: 14.

03:36:33.533 --> 03:36:34.660
TALIESIN: At disadvantage?

03:36:34.660 --> 03:36:35.519
SAM: No. Just me.

03:36:35.519 --> 03:36:36.623
TALIESIN: Oh, 16.

03:36:36.623 --> 03:36:38.300
MATT: Roll for Yasha as well.

03:36:39.437 --> 03:36:42.269
TRAVIS: Five for her.

03:36:42.269 --> 03:36:49.987
MATT: Oof. All right, overall party: not so great.
It takes you a little while, about two to three

03:36:49.987 --> 03:36:55.389
hours of searching the bottom of the ocean. You're
starting to get a little hungry again from all the

03:36:55.389 --> 03:37:01.943
strenuous activity of moving and dragging these
cannonballs with you to keep you weighted down so

03:37:01.943 --> 03:37:07.312
you can step across the surface. You come past
some deep sea corals and beautiful colorful

03:37:07.312 --> 03:37:13.016
visions and schools of fish scooting and coasting
around. At one point, they swarm past you, and you

03:37:13.016 --> 03:37:20.303
feel them tickling past your torso before they
skitter past. Eventually, this lift begins to

03:37:20.303 --> 03:37:28.791
descend into a small bowl or at least a point
where the shelf begins to head in a downward

03:37:28.791 --> 03:37:36.773
direction at a decline. Within the next 15 or so
minutes of traveling in that direction, you see

03:37:36.773 --> 03:37:43.141
the outline of a familiar ship.

03:37:43.141 --> 03:37:47.813
TRAVIS: I push forward towards it. Point and start
to swim.

03:37:47.813 --> 03:37:54.139
MATT: All right. As you all gather in behind Fjord
making your way in the direction of this long

03:37:54.139 --> 03:37:56.687
forgotten shipwreck, we'll pick it up there next
week.

03:37:56.687 --> 03:37:59.420
(groaning)

03:38:01.093 --> 03:38:03.145
MATT: You'll find out next week!

03:38:03.145 --> 03:38:04.257
SAM: Oh my god, Matt.

03:38:04.257 --> 03:38:06.379
MARISHA and TRAVIS: What a game!

03:38:06.379 --> 03:38:07.753
MATT: That was a good session, guys.

03:38:07.753 --> 03:38:14.719
LIAM: One of the best ever. So many great games!

03:38:14.719 --> 03:38:21.766
MATT: That went some interesting places. There's a
number of scenarios that didn't happen.

03:38:21.766 --> 03:38:25.413
TRAVIS: There was a number of scenarios that
didn't happen?

03:38:25.413 --> 03:38:28.634
SAM: I feel like there was so much more on the
island that we did not--

03:38:28.634 --> 03:38:30.113
MATT: There's a lot more on that island.

03:38:30.113 --> 03:38:35.014
SAM: There's Allison, there was shit alleys, and
there was all kinds of fun stuff.

03:38:35.014 --> 03:38:38.643
TALIESIN: Just because we're banished doesn't mean
we're never going back.

03:38:38.643 --> 03:38:41.198
MARISHA: We keep pissing off the towns.

03:38:41.198 --> 03:38:45.903
TALIESIN: Oh, I'm so sorry. Like a cop said
"you're trespassing" and now we're just going to

03:38:45.903 --> 03:38:47.468
never trespass again?

03:38:47.468 --> 03:38:48.351
TRAVIS: Well said.

03:38:48.351 --> 03:38:51.602
MATT: Yes, we're not because we're law abiding
citizens.

03:38:51.602 --> 03:38:55.853
MARISHA: I was going to say, when you go into a
convenience store and it's got the "Have you seen

03:38:55.853 --> 03:38:57.417
"this person?"

03:38:57.417 --> 03:38:59.646
LIAM: This campaign is a social experiment.

03:38:59.646 --> 03:39:05.991
MATT: Oh yeah. This has gone really interesting,
fun places. Well, thank you guys. I'm excited to

03:39:05.991 --> 03:39:15.278
pick this up next week at the shipwreck. Thank you
guys for tuning in. Yeah, I missed this-- two

03:39:15.278 --> 03:39:17.600
weeks off and suddenly--

03:39:17.600 --> 03:39:19.041
LIAM: All the dead.

03:39:19.041 --> 03:39:20.978
TALIESIN: We were freaking out all for two weeks
straight.

03:39:20.978 --> 03:39:21.919
LAURA: Yeah.

03:39:21.919 --> 03:39:24.025
MATT: You guys had some good, solid plans.

03:39:24.025 --> 03:39:26.580
MARISHA: Our plan was okay.

03:39:26.580 --> 03:39:27.501
MATT: Yeah.

03:39:27.501 --> 03:39:32.022
TALIESIN: That was entirely worth the amount of
data it took up on my phone.

03:39:32.022 --> 03:39:33.685
LIAM: It worked.

03:39:33.685 --> 03:39:37.215
TRAVIS: I think all anyone asked is for some
slight improvements in our planning over the

03:39:37.215 --> 03:39:38.940
years. Slight improvements.

03:39:38.940 --> 03:39:40.572
LIAM: Yeah, it worked.

03:39:40.572 --> 03:39:45.664
MATT: Man, most of D&amp;D is about plans that go
fucking tits up the minute you try and talk about

03:39:45.664 --> 03:39:52.482
it. Everyone is like, "Oh, they planned so
terribly." Every D&amp;D game, everyone plans

03:39:52.482 --> 03:39:57.390
terribly. Sometimes plans go great, and those are
the ones you remember when you compare it to other

03:39:57.390 --> 03:40:02.028
people. "Oh, we're great planners. Remember that
two times over the past 18 years we played where

03:40:02.028 --> 03:40:06.980
"our plans went great? Those are the times we'll
always bring up and judging other people's plans."

03:40:06.980 --> 03:40:10.839
Yeah, everyone has some good plans every now and
then. More often than not, plans go pretty shitty

03:40:10.839 --> 03:40:17.889
and that's fun. Anyway, thank you all for coming
and watching along with us after the two week

03:40:17.889 --> 03:40:25.448
break. Thank you D&amp;D Beyond for being our amazing
friends and sponsors. We'll see you in a week and

03:40:25.448 --> 03:40:27.937
remember we love you all--

03:40:27.937 --> 03:40:33.620
LIAM: (creepy voice) Is it Thursday yet?
(growling)

03:40:33.620 --> 03:40:35.393
MARISHA: You did this.

03:40:35.393 --> 03:40:37.235
SAM: Yeah, I did.

03:40:37.235 --> 03:40:38.340
MARISHA: This is you.

03:40:38.340 --> 03:40:39.681
SAM: Sorry.

03:40:39.681 --> 03:40:42.880
LIAM: I'm so upset. (normal voice) Take it away,
Matt.

03:40:42.880 --> 03:40:45.919
MATT: Is it Thursday yet? Good night, everybody.

03:40:45.919 --> 03:40:49.175
(laughter)

03:40:49.175 --> 03:40:56.707
[music]